# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: criticism-of-tesco
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The 2013 horsemeat scandal was a food fraud crisis that began on 15 January 2013 when it was reported that a wide range of food products advertised in the European Union as containing beef were found to contain undeclared or improperly declared horse meat.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The crisis escalated in February 2013 when some Findus products were found to contain up to 100% horsemeat instead of beef.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] A smaller number of products also contained other undeclared meats, such as pork.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The issue was discovered through DNA testing on frozen beefburgers and lasagne sold in several Irish and British supermarkets.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The analysis found that 23 out of 27 beef burger samples also contained pig DNA.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Adherents of some religions are forbidden from eating pork or horse meat due to their beliefs.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] While the presence of undeclared meat was not a health issue, the scandal revealed a major breakdown in the traceability of the food supply chain and the risk that harmful ingredients could have been included.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Sports horses, for example, could have entered the food supply chain, and with them the veterinary drug phenylbutazone, which is banned in food animals.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The scandal later spread to 13 other European countries, and European authorities decided to find an EU-wide solution.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] They initiated meat testing of about 4,000 horse meat samples for the veterinary drug.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Investigations by the Food Safety Authority of Ireland (FSAI) led Ireland to become the first EU state to report the presence of horse meat in beef and to make the results public.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The first positive test for equine DNA was on 10 December 2012.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] It carried out additional tests on 18 and 21 December.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The FSAI then sent samples to the Eurofins laboratory in Germany.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Professor Alan Reilly of the FSAI testified to the Oireachtas on 5 February 2013 that the results indicated the presence of equine DNA, but not the amount.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The IdentiGen Laboratory and the Eurofins Laboratory were asked to determine the amount of horse meat in the samples.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On 21 December 2012, the FSAI requested that the Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine in Ireland obtain further samples.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] These were sent to the IdentiGen laboratory on 4 January 2013.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Results were received back from Eurofins and IdentiGen on 11 January 2013.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Professor Reilly reported on 5 February that quantitative results from IdentiGen were received by the FSAI late on the evening of 11 January 2013.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Of the ten burger products that tested positive for equine DNA, all but one were at low levels.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The quantification of equine DNA in this burger product estimated 29% relative to the beef DNA content.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Silvercrest manufactured this product on behalf of Tesco.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] At this point, there was no explanation for the finding of 29% equine DNA relative to beef DNA in this single sample.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On 14 January 2013, the FSAI informed the Department of Health and the Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine of the final results.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On the same day, it also informed the Food Standards Agency in the United Kingdom.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The next day, 15 January 2013, the FSAI advised the five retailers concerned, Tesco, Dunnes Stores, Aldi, Lidl and Iceland, of their findings; all these firms withdrew the offending products.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The media and newspapers of 16 January 2013 led with the story, focusing on the one burger which tested positive for 29% equine DNA.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Another significant investigation into the horse meat affair in Ireland, by Ireland's Department of Agriculture, published its findings in March 2013.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] In the UK, a House of Commons Select Committee on Environment, Food and Rural Affairs report on the horse meat incident was not critical of UK or Irish producers.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] It expressed concern that horsemeat contamination resulted from fraud and other criminal activity across the EU.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The second major UK report on the horse meat incident was conducted by Professor Chris Elliott, the Director of the Institute for Global Food Security at Queen's University Belfast.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] In his independent report, he argues that food crime was at the heart of the horsemeat incident and makes a range of suggestions for how this could be tackled.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Of 27 beef burger products tested, 37% were positive for horse DNA, and 85% were positive for pig DNA.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Of 31 beef meal products tested, 21 were positive for pig DNA, but all were negative for horse DNA.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Nineteen salami products were tested, but were negative for all foreign DNA.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Of the 37% of beef products tested positive for horse DNA, Tesco's Everyday Value Beef Burgers tested at 29.1%.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] All other reported brands had less than 0.3% horse DNA.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] These products originated from Liffey Meats and Silvercrest Foods in Ireland, and from the Dalepak Hambleton food processing plant in the United Kingdom.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Trace amounts of horse DNA were also found in raw ingredients imported from Spain and the Netherlands.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Laboratory DNA investigations were requested by the authorities into possible donkey meat adulteration of minced meat products labelled as 100% beef.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] British company Primerdesign provided many of the tests to laboratories and companies wishing to test for contamination.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] By 16 January 2013, four subsidiaries of ABP Food Group had been accused of supplying adulterated meat.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] They were Silvercrest in County Monaghan, Dalepak in North Yorkshire, Freshlink in Glasgow, ABP Nenagh in County Tipperary, Ireland, and Dairy Crest, Rossington.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Hamburger meat from Silvercrest Foods, a subsidiary of Larry Goodman's ABP Food Group, in County Monaghan, Ireland, was found to contain 29% horse meat relative to beef.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Tesco dropped Silvercrest as a supplier of processed meat, but ABP said that it "welcomed their decision to continue sourcing fresh beef from other ABP companies".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The first apparent instance of fresh beef being adulterated with horse meat was reported by Asda, which removed its 500-gram own-label beef Bolognese sauce from sale.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The sauce was supplied by Greencore, which said in a statement that the meat in the sauce had been supplied by ABP Food Group's Nenagh plant in County Tipperary, Ireland.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Burger King, which had more than 500 fast food outlets in Ireland and the UK at the time, dropped Silvercrest as a supplier, using suppliers in Germany and Italy instead, after horse meat was found in their supply chain.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Waitrose removed beef meatballs from sale when it found that they contained pork.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The meatballs were manufactured by an ABP factory in Glasgow.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Waitrose, part of John Lewis, said it would be creating a new facility to supply its own beef products.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Tesco, the Co-operative Group, Iceland, and Aldi also cancelled their contracts with ABP Food Group due to the adulteration.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Food wholesaler Makro, supplier to the restaurant and pub industry, announced that some of its frozen burgers supplied by Silvercrest tested positive for horse DNA.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] A spokesman said that Makro no longer sells the product in question.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On 14 February 2013, the French government stated that a French meat-processing company, À la Table de Spanghero, had knowingly sold horse meat labelled as beef, and that its licence was suspended while an inquiry was underway.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Spanghero imported meat from Romania and sold it on to another French company, Comigel, which made frozen ready meals at its factory in Luxembourg.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] French Consumer Affairs Minister Benoît Hamon said the meat had left Romania clearly and correctly labelled as horse and that it was afterwards that it was relabelled as beef by Spanghero.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The investigation also said some blame may rest with Comigel, claiming the staff there should have noticed anomalies in the paperwork, and realised from the smell and look of the meat once it was defrosted that it was not beef.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On 7 February 2013, Findus announced that in a sample of 18 beef lasagne products that it tested, 11 contained between 60% and 100% horse meat.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] It was also revealed that some of the products sold had minced meat declared as beef that was 60–100% horse meat.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The source of the horse meat was third party supplier Comigel, a French-headquartered frozen ready meal producer, from its subsidiary Tavola factory in Capellen, Luxembourg.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] According to the FSA, the company had been alerted by a third-party French supplier on 4 February 2013, and it tested its beef lasagne products, finding that over 50% of the products tested contained horse meat.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] According to reports, both Findus UK and the French supplier withdrew all products related to the third-party supplier.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The reason for the adulteration was initially stated as "highly likely" criminal activity.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The president of Comigel, Erick Lehagre, told Agence France-Presse that the adulterated meat supplier was Spanghero, a firm owned by Lur Berri and founded in 1970 by Claude and Laurent Spanghero, two former France international rugby players.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] He said that Spanghero had told him that the meat was not from France, but came from a producer in Romania.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On 11 February 2013, France's Consumer Affairs Minister Benoit Hamon warned it "will not hesitate" to take legal action if there is evidence companies had knowingly duped consumers.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Hamon said an initial investigation by French safety authorities had found that a French company, Poujol (Spanghero's holding company), had bought frozen meat from a Cypriot trader.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] That trader had bought it from Dutch food supplier Draap (the Dutch word for horse, *paard*, spelled backwards), owned by Jan Fasen, who was previously convicted in 2012 of horsemeat fraud dating back to 2007.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Draap, in turn, bought it from two Romanian slaughterhouses.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Poujol then supplied a factory in Luxembourg, owned by Comigel, which then supplied Findus and the British supermarkets.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The Romanian government has stated that there are no contracts between the Romanian abattoirs and any French, Cypriot, or Dutch meat processors.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On 8 February 2013, Findus announced that it would no longer accept meat from Comigel and stopped further deliveries of the product in question.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On the same day, Findus UK published a public apology on its website, also announcing that, following DNA testing, three of its products were found to contain horse tissue.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] These are the 320, 350, and 500 gram packages of Findus Beef Lasagne; the company offered a refund for products purchased.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Findus Sverige AB also announced a recall of its 375 gram packs of ready-made single-portion lasagne (code 63957), and published a contact number for customers who had already purchased the products.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On 8 February 2013, supermarket chain Aldi announced that it would withdraw from sale Today's Special Frozen Beef Lasagne and Today's Special Frozen Spaghetti Bolognese, supplied by Comigel, after tests found the meat content to be between 30 and 100% horse.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The Swiss-based company Nestlé reported on 18 February 2013 that it had found more than 1% horse DNA in two beef pasta products.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] It withdrew chilled pasta products, Buitoni Beef Ravioli and Beef Tortellini, in Italy and Spain.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Sourced from sub-contractor HJ Schypke, itself a German sub-contractor of Belgian-based Nestlé supplier JBS Toledo, also withdrew frozen Lasagnes à la Bolognaise Gourmandes, a product for catering businesses produced in France.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On 22 February 2013, Birds Eye revealed that DNA tests showed that horse meat was present in Birds Eye chili con carne sold in Belgium and supplied by Belgium firm Frigilunch.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Birds Eye withdrew three ready meals that contained beef from sale in the UK.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] All of the frozen beef products produced by Sodexo, "one of the largest private catering businesses in Britain", were withdrawn on 22 February 2013 following the discovery of horse DNA in a sample.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The company supplies 2,300 institutions within the UK, including schools, old-age people's homes, prisons, and branches of the armed forces.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On 1 March, the Department of Food and Veterinary of Lithuania announced that horse meat was found in three canned beef brands sold by Latvian company Kuršu Zeme.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Canned beef made by the Latvian company was removed from sale in Lithuania.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On 10 April 2013, it was reported that two Dutch trading companies, owned by the same person whom food safety officials had previously investigated, may have supplied 50,000 metric tonnes of adulterated beef containing horse meat since January 2011.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On 7 February 2013, it was revealed by the Food Standards Agency that the Findus beef lasagne range in the UK, France, Norway, and Sweden, and the shepherd's pie and moussaka ranges in France, contained horse meat without proper declaration or official scrutiny.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The contamination may have gone on since summer 2012 according to a leaked document.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Compass Group was the world's biggest catering firm at the time and discovered through conducting tests that it was unknowingly supplying concealed horse meat in food products to a "small number" of schools in Northern Ireland.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Whitbread, which was at the time Britain's biggest hotel group, also discovered through tests that it had unknowingly sold concealed horse meat in food products.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The horse meat that was found in Comigel products originated at Doly Com, a Romanian-based slaughterhouse.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] An inquiry by the French government showed that "the meat had left Romania clearly and correctly labelled as horse.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] It was afterwards that it was relabelled as beef." Doly Com supplied the horse meat under a contract to Cyprus-based Draap Trading Ltd, a meat trader which operates in the Netherlands.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] It is owned by a British Virgin Islands holding company, and Jan Fasen is a director.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] *Draap* spelt backwards is *paard,* the Dutch word for *horse*.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] After having the horse meat delivered to a cold storage company in Breda, Draap then sold the frozen meat to Spanghero, who insist that it arrived at their Castelnaudary plant labelled as "Beef – originating in EU".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] After some processing, Spanghero then sent it to Comigel, where the end products for sale were made.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] According to French media reports, Spanghero falsified documents regarding the meat.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Horse meat found in Silvercrest products is thought to have originated in Poland.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] A small survey, part of the EU-funded project FoodRisC, conducted by a team from University College Dublin and Brunel University found that health risks were not respondents' first concern; rather, the claims made on labels did not match the contents of food products.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Additional concerns included allegations that a "French plant which handled horse meat sold in Britain as beef has previously been at the centre of a major E.coli discovery".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Inquiry into horse meat sources in the UK also revealed that Aintree racecourse has a contract with a licensed slaughterhouse in West Yorkshire to remove dead Grand National race horses.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] It is illegal for horses euthanised by injection to be put into the human food chain.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Many chemical agents used for animal euthanasia leave residues in the meat, which may be harmful to humans, and have caused sickness and death in predators and scavengers.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] In January 2013, concerns first arose about the possibility that horse meat containing traces of the veterinary drug phenylbutazone could enter the human food chain, despite regulations that horses treated with it cannot legally be used for human consumption.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The drug, commonly known as "bute", is used as an analgesic in horses.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The issue was also raised by politicians such as Labour party MP Mary Creagh.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] In response, the Food Standards Agency (FSA) initially stated that only five cases of horses slaughtered in the UK had been treated with phenylbutazone, none of which had entered the human food chain.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] A subsequent review of 206 horse carcasses slaughtered in the UK between 30 January and 7 February 2013 found eight were contaminated with phenylbutazone, six of which had been shipped to France.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The UK's Chief Medical Officer, Sally Davies, said the level of contamination, 1.9 mg/kg, posed "very little risk to human health".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] She added that around 500–600 burgers containing 100% horse meat would need to be eaten to receive the daily human therapeutic dose.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Additional tests at that time indicated than none of the products from Findus contained phenylbutazone.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Another report found that between two and five percent of samples tested between 2007 and 2011 had phenylbutazone contamination, and that only 50 samples per year were tested.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] In 2012, 145 carcasses were tested, and two of the nine carcasses that tested positive for bute that year were not reported to the FSA for seven months.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] However, one problem raised was over-documentation; all UK animals with phenylbutazone contamination tested in early 2013 possessed a "horse passport" that allowed their carcasses to be sold for human consumption.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The veterinary residues committee (VRC) reminded the public in July 2012 that it had been "repeatedly expressing concern" about phenylbutazone contamination. and recent discoveries of contamination suggest that the passport system was not working.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Phenylbutazone is used therapeutically in humans as a treatment for ankylosing spondylitis when other treatments are not suitable.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The effect on humans of low-level exposure over an extended period has not been extensively formally studied.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] High incidences of focal necrosis were found in female rats fed low doses of 1,2-diphenylhydrazine over time.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID) residues risk causing rare, but potentially fatal side-effects in humans.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] There is inadequate data on carcinogenicity of phenylbutazone; it is not classifiable as to its carcinogenicity to humans.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] There is also speculation that some horse meat from the United States, where phenylbutazone is commonly used, may have entered the food chain via Mexico and then been exported to Europe.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] One reason for this is that Spanghero had purchased meat from a company, Draap, whose owner, Jan Fasen was previously convicted for fraud; as long ago as 2007, Draap had labelled horse meat imported from Mexico and South America as Dutch or German beef.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] These animals may have meat too toxic to eat safely.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Some experts and UK government officials have raised concerns that horse meat from Romania could be contaminated with equine infectious anaemia (EIA).
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Although EIA does not pose a risk to humans, it could be an indicator of additional health problems in horses that may stem from poor living conditions.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Since 2007, the European Union has restricted export of live horses from Romania to any other EU member state unless the animals have a Coggins test for EIA prior to export.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Environment secretary Owen Paterson stated that "Romanian horse meat is not allowed in", though he acknowledged that it could be a serious problem if Romanian horse meat from animals with EIA had been imported.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Some news outlets referred to EIA as "Horse AIDS", even though it is not an immunodeficiency syndrome and the retrovirus that causes it is equid-specific.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] EIA is, however, a lentivirus, like HIV, and thus research on EIA has the potential to help research efforts with HIV/AIDS.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] An article by Will Hutton about contamination in the UK lays much of the responsibility at the door of those who have removed much of the regulation of the meat industry, and cut the budgets and workforces—halving the number of inspectors—of those responsible for enforcing the remaining regulations.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Another article points out that "Long business supply chains are corruptible and can hide a multitude of crimes if no one checks for fraud or criminal activity".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] In Britain, the incident was a catalyst for the discussion of the validity of a self-regulated meat industry.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Karen Jennings, assistant general secretary of the UNISON trades union, said that "the industry isn't fit to regulate itself".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Observant Muslims and Jews consider it sinful to eat certain types of meat, pork for both groups, and also horse and many other animals for Jews, due to religious prohibitions.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Professor Reilly stated "for some religious groups or people who abstain from eating pig meat, the presence of traces of pig DNA is unacceptable".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On 15 March 2013, a Westminster health and safety survey confirmed that pig DNA had been found in halal chicken sausages produced for schools.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Horse meat is not normally eaten in Ireland and Britain.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] According to Professor Reilly, chief executive of the FSAI, "In Ireland, it is not our culture to eat horse meat and therefore, we do not expect to find it in a burger".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Silvercrest, a subsidiary of ABP Foods has claimed that there is no risk to the public upon eating the foreign meat.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Eleven firms, including Tesco and Asda, said they shared shoppers' "anger and outrage".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Whitbread vowed to remedy the unacceptable situation.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The Food Standards Agency's (FSA) chief executive, Catherine Brown also said "it is unlikely we will ever know" how many unwittingly ate horsemeat.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Tesco's market value dropped by €360 million.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] European Union officials, European ministers and Commissioner (Tonio) Borg set up an urgent meeting in Brussels on 13 February 2013 on how to contain the horse meat scandal that exposed flaws in European control systems on food safety, and to formulate an action plan.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Following the meeting, EU agriculture ministers announced a three-month coordinated control plan of DNA testing of processed meat across the European Union.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The plan, adopted 19 February 2013, called for 2,500 random tests on processed food for horse DNA and 4,000 for phenylbutazone (bute), beginning in March 2013, with initial results announced on 15 April 2013.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The Hague-based Europol would handle the co-ordination of investigations among national authorities, as well as any raids on premises and arrests on suspicion of criminal conspiracy to defraud.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On 26 February 2013, it was announced that sales of frozen hamburgers had fallen by 43% and frozen ready meals by 13% from pre-scandal levels.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The study took place 21 January – 17 February.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Sales of *bona fide* horse meat, on the other hand, increased in those EU countries where it is moderately common.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On 23 May 2013, a Dutch meat wholesaler, Willy Selten, was arrested for allegedly selling 300 tonnes of horsemeat as beef.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Selten, who owns the meat wholesaler Willy Selten BV, was arrested together with the company's interim director.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] In October, Barry Gardiner MP, the UK shadow Environment minister, criticised the lack of prosecutions of leading players ten months after David Cameron had promised that everything possible would be done to deal with a "very shocking" crime.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On 26 August 2016, Andronicos Sideras, owner of Dinos and Sons Ltd, was charged with conspiring with Ulrich Nielsen and Alex Ostler-Beech, of Flexi Foods, to sell horsemeat as beef between 1 January 2012 – 31 October 2012 by the City of London Police.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On 2 August 2017 Sideras was jailed for four years and six months and Nielsen for three years and six months, while Ostler-Beech was given an 18-month suspended sentence and a 120 hour-community service order.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] In December 2013, consignments of horse meat were seized, and arrests were made.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] 21 people were arrested on Monday, 16 December, in various parts of southern France.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] This meat was from horses kept on a farm attached to a scientific laboratory and not certified as fit for human consumption.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2013-horse-meat-scandal] A dealer from Narbonne was helping police with enquiries.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] In late 2021, the prices of many essential goods in the United Kingdom began increasing faster than household incomes, resulting in a fall in real incomes.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] The phenomenon has been termed a cost-of-living crisis.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] It is due in part to the economic impact of the COVID-19 pandemic, including a global surge in inflation, wage stagnation attributed to the Conservative Party's austerity programme, as well as the economic instability caused by Brexit and the Russo-Ukrainian war.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] While all in the UK are affected by rising prices, the crisis most substantially affects people living in poverty.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] The British government has responded with measures including grants, tax rebates, and subsidies to electricity and gas suppliers.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] Regular pay began to outpace inflation beginning in May 2023, but living costs have remained at elevated levels, and have continued to increase faster than headline inflation into 2025.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] The Joseph Rowntree Foundation projected in 2025 that disposable incomes would continue to decline for the rest of the decade.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] By January 2024, the 12-month Retail Price Index had fallen to 4% after peaking at 11.1% in October 2022, while workers' wages had risen 6.2% in the last quarter of 2023.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] In late 2023, the Resolution Foundation estimated that household incomes would not return to pre-crisis levels until at least 2027.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] Both global and local factors have contributed to the UK's cost-of-living crisis.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] According to Bank of England governor Andrew Bailey, about 80% of the causes driving the cost-of-living crisis are global.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] These include the various forms of instability the world has experienced in the early 2020s such as the COVID-19 pandemic, a chip shortage, an energy crisis, a supply chain crisis, and Russia's invasion of Ukraine.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] In 2021, the UK's inflation was less than that of the US, but high US inflation was not generally experienced as a cost-of-living crisis due to the stimulus cheques that had been distributed to American households.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] Britain suffered from wage stagnation after 2008, which has been attributed to the austerity programme.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] There has been no other comparable period of economic stagnation in Britain since records began during the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] Pay stagnation was particularly felt among younger demographics in the 2010s, but was not considered a major political issue until later in the decade.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] The middle class was sheltered from the effects of this at the time due to near-zero interest rates, and it did not affect pensioners – the core base of the Conservative party – as this group was already retired.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] This contributed to a lack of urgency during the Conservative-led governments of the era.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] The government of Theresa May did attempt to address this in the late 2010s with her targeting of those who could "just about manage"; stagnation was likely the impetus behind Boris Johnson's "levelling up" agenda.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] Other local effects include labour shortages related to foreign workers leaving due to Brexit, and additional taxes on households.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] Factors that have worsened the crisis since 1 April 2022 include Ofgem increasing the household energy price cap by 54%, an increase in National Insurance and a rise in Council Tax.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] Researchers in the Centre for Economic Performance at the London School of Economics investigated trade flows and consumer prices of food products in the UK and found Brexit increased food prices due to increased red tape when food is imported from Europe.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] This affected poorer households disproportionately.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] Unemployed people in the UK receive lower fiscal support than the average for OECD countries; UK salaries have not risen substantially since the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] Insufficient long-term gas storage facilities left UK energy prices overexposed to market fluctuations.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] Household income, whether from wages or benefits, has not generally kept pace with rising prices.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] In April 2022, UK real wages fell by 4.5%, the sharpest fall since records began back in 2001.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] By July 2022, inflation had risen to over 10%, the highest level in 40 years, and the Bank of England was forecasting it could reach 13% by the end of the year.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] Energy costs for the typical British household were expected to rise 80% from October 2022, from £1,971 to £3,549, until Liz Truss, who was Prime Minister at the time, announced measures to limit these increases.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] On 23 September 2022, UK Chancellor Kwasi Kwarteng announced his mini-budget, backed by Truss, which included widespread tax cuts.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] The package included cuts to stamp duty and the abolition of the 45% income tax rate for those earning £150,000 or more a year.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] These cuts aimed to encourage foreign investment and economic growth but were not costed and spooked financial markets, causing the pound to fall to a low of $1.03.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] The Bank of England responded by raising interest rates, which caused mortgage payments to increase significantly.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] By late October 2022, Truss and Kwarteng had been replaced by Rishi Sunak and Jeremy Hunt, respectively, and all of the mini-budget's proposals had effectively been cancelled.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] The pound regained some strength by this point, but interest rates remained high, stretching household incomes.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] Inflation began rising sharply in 2021, affecting a wide range of goods and services.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] Transport costs have been especially affected, as have many others, including food, furniture, household items, electricity, and clothing.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] The *Financial Times* reported in May 2022 that the crisis caused UK consumer confidence to fall to its lowest level since 1974.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] In June, charities had reported the crisis is affecting people's mental health, with one publishing a survey where 9% of responding parents had said their children had begun self-harming.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] Based on an Office for National Statistics (ONS) survey performed between 27 April and 22 May 2022, 77% of UK adults reported feeling worried about the rising cost of living, with 50% saying they worried "nearly every day".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] A separate ONS survey taken from 25 May to 5 June found 52% of respondents had cut back on their energy use.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] While rising prices have affected all social classes, people experiencing poverty have been impacted the most.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] According to a survey by the *Food Foundation* think tank published in February 2022, one million UK adults went a whole day without eating over the past month.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] The ONS reported that in the year to September 2022, there was a 22% increase in shoplifting.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] In response, some supermarkets installed new retail loss prevention systems that require customers to scan their printed receipt on an optical scanner as proof of purchase before they can exit the store.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] The systems have attracted some negative public reaction.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] On 10 November 2022, nurses and other medical personnel across the NHS voted to strike, under the Royal College of Nursing.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] The nurses stated this was due to failing wages, inflation, overwork, and underfunding.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] The industrial action affected NHS hospitals throughout the UK.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] Nurses were still expected to work certain days at reduced capacity to ensure the NHS remained operational.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] As lower-income households spend a greater share of their income on food and energy, two of the more rapidly inflating areas, these households face a higher effective inflation rate than the wealthy.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] In November 2022, this meant that the wealthier households were experiencing inflation of 9.6%, while poorer households experienced 12.5%.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] This gap in the effective inflation rate across income brackets was the highest on record.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] Due to heating costs, the effective inflation rate for those aged over 80 was 15.3% The Office for National Statistics (ONS) stated on 11 November that business investment fell during the three months to September and was below the pre-pandemic levels.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] Gross domestic product fell during the three months to September due to a decline in manufacturing "across most industries" according to the ONS.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] On 8 December 2022, *The Guardian* reported that according to research by the Joseph Rowntree Foundation, over 3 million UK low-income households could not afford to heat their homes.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] According to the foundation's research, roughly 710,000 households had difficulty paying for food, heating, and warm clothing.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] The foundation urged the government to increase Universal Credit.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] A government spokesperson said that support for the most vulnerable remained a priority and that millions of the most needy people were being given at least £1,200 in direct payments to protect them against rising prices, in addition to the £400 being given to each household towards energy costs.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] The spokesperson said that the support also included a winter energy price guarantee worth approximately £900 for a typical household, a household support fund to help with essential costs, and that the chancellor had announced further efforts to support those most in need in the following year.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] Unpaid energy bills controversially led energy companies to switch customers to (more expensive) prepayment meters.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] *The Times* found that in some cases, energy companies forced their way into homes to install the hardware.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] Ofgem responded by temporarily banning the practice in February 2023, until new regulations were imposed in January 2024.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] In May 2025, Ofgem announced that eight suppliers would pay compensation to 40,000 customers who had been affected by "inappropriate installation".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] The Joseph Rowntree Foundation said their research showed that hundreds of thousands of households could not afford to protect themselves from cold and that prices of essentials were rising steeply, with energy bills nearly double the level of the previous winter.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] On 5 September 2023, Birmingham City Council, the largest local authority in Europe, issued a Section 114 notice declaring itself effectively bankrupt.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] In May 2024, the 12-Month CPI, which is the official measure of inflation in consumer prices in the United Kingdom, reduced to the official Bank of England target of 2%.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] Inflation remained at the target only briefly and had returned to 3% by the end of 2024, with living costs still elevated.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] While theft in general remained far lower than its peak in the early 1990s, shoplifting has continued to increase rapidly.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] A 20% increase in 2024 led to a record high for shoplifting, seen particularly among older demographics.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] April 2025 was nicknamed "awful April" by several media outlets, noting above-inflation increases in many household bills, chiefly water and energy.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] These bill increases included an average 26.1% increase in water and sewage bills, the fastest increase since the late 1980s.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] Inflation reached 3.8% in July 2025, far lower than the 11.1% seen in October 2022 but still above the 2% target.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] It was expected to reach 4% in September, but remained at 3.8% for 3 consecutive months, before falling to 3.6% in October 2025.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] Food inflation in particular was at 4.9% in July 2025, which is particularly problematic for low-income households.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] Early government responses to rising inflation included a 6.6% increase in the minimum wage, announced in 2021 and effective in April 2022.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] The UK government intensified its efforts to address the cost-of-living crisis in May 2022, introducing a £5 billion windfall tax on energy companies to help fund a £15 billion support package for the public.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] The package included every household receiving a £400 discount on energy bills, in addition to a £150 council tax refund that the government had already ordered.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] For about 8 million of the UK's lowest-income households, a further £650 payment was announced.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] Additionally, pensioners or those with disability would qualify for extra payments, on top of the £550 that every household gets, and the £650 they would receive if they had a low income.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] In June 2022, business secretary Kwasi Kwarteng ordered an urgent review of the motor fuel market, to be completed by 7 July, to determine whether consumer prices were excessively high.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] The measures were called insufficient by many people and organisations, including outgoing Prime Minister Boris Johnson, with the Bank of England predicting that the UK would enter recession by 2023.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] Johnson's successor Liz Truss announced a package of subsidies to address rising energy bills, with an estimated cost of up to £150 billion, depending on future wholesale prices.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] The main piece of this package was the Energy Price Guarantee, which would mean that a UK household with "average energy usage" would pay no more than £2,500 a year on energy, although this was widely misinterpreted as Truss stated in media interviews that "nobody would pay more than £2,500".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] She later clarified this, while ruling out introducing a new windfall tax on the profits of energy producers and suppliers.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] After he was appointed prime minister in October 2022 following Truss's resignation amid an economic and credibility crisis caused by the September 2022 mini-budget proposed by Truss and Kwarteng, Rishi Sunak continued the package of subsidies for rising energy bills.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] As chancellor, he provided some funding to help vulnerable people cope with the rising cost of living.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] In October 2022, the Scottish government introduced an act to freeze rents and establish a moratorium on evictions in Scotland for both the private rented and social sectors.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] Various campaigns, such as Don't Pay UK, were established to encourage the government to implement further assistance.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] The campaigner Jack Monroe warned that the crisis could be fatal for some of the children of low-income parents, and asked the government to increase benefits in line with inflation.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] On 18 June 2022, thousands of workers marched to Parliament in London to demand further government action for the cost-of-living crisis.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] A campaign called "Enough is Enough" was organised by trade union leaders to lobby during the crisis.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] Its demands include a return to pre-April 2022 energy rates, a real-terms pay rise for public sector workers, a rise in the national minimum wage, a reversal of the National Insurance increase, and a £20-per-week increase in Universal Credit payments.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] Within a few weeks of its August 2022 launch, almost 450,000 people had joined the movement.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] It gained some high-profile supporters, including the Mayor of Greater Manchester Andy Burnham and US Senator Bernie Sanders.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] In November 2023, The Trussell Trust calculated that a single adult in the UK in 2023 needs at least £29,500 a year to have an acceptable standard of living, up from £25,000 in 2022.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] Two partners with two children would need £50,000, compared to £44,500 in 2022.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] Twenty-nine per cent of the UK population—which works out to 19.2 million people—belong to households that bring in below a minimum figure.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] The Green Party of England and Wales supports increasing Universal Credit and implementing a home insulation scheme to reduce energy use and cut fuel bills as part of its stance on the cost-of-living crisis.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] It also supports lowering the costs of public transport, providing 35 hours a week free child care from the age of nine months and a pay increase for public sector workers to match inflation.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] The cost-of-living crisis has been noted by the media, as well as workers' unions, as one of the reasons for industrial action by staff in industries such as the railway strikes, bus strikes and action by legal aid lawyers.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] In September 2022, the BBC soap opera *Doctors* began covering the topic in a long-running issue-led storyline featuring Scarlett Kiernan (Kia Pegg) and her father struggling to survive.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/2021-present-united-kingdom-cost-of-living-crisis] In October 2022, the BBC unveiled its new brand, *Tackling It Together*, designed to help consumers navigate the cost-of-living crisis.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/a-place-at-the-table] Participant Media is the entertainment company behind the film, and it is distributed by Magnolia Pictures.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/a-place-at-the-table] The Participant/Magnolia team is also responsible for the film *Food, Inc.* (2008).
[src:criticism-of-tesco/a-place-at-the-table] The film was originally titled *Finding North* but the name was later changed to *A Place at the Table*.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/a-place-at-the-table] As of 2012, about 50 million Americans were food insecure.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/a-place-at-the-table] This was approximately 1 in 6 of the overall population, with the proportion of children facing food insecurity even higher at about 1 in 4.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/a-place-at-the-table] One in every two children receive federal food assistance.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/a-place-at-the-table] Other Americans struggling with hunger are also featured, including a cop whose monthly paychecks only leaves him enough money to buy food for two weeks, forcing him to use a food bank.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/a-place-at-the-table] There is also a companion book titled *A Place at the Table: The Crisis of 49 Million Hungry Americans and How to Solve It,* edited by Peter Pringle and published by Public Affairs.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/a-place-at-the-table] The book features contributions from Jeff Bridges, Ken Cook, Marion Nestle, Bill Shore, Joel Berg, Robert Egger, Janet Poppendieck, David Beckmann, Mariana Chilton, Tom Colicchio, Jennifer Harris, Andy Fisher, Kelly Meyer and directors Kristi Jacobson and Lori Silverbush.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/a-place-at-the-table] The film was nominated for Grand Jury Prize at the 2012 Sundance Film Festival.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/a-place-at-the-table] At the 2013 IDA Documentary Awards, the film received the Pare Lorentz Award, which recognizes films for model filmmaking while focusing on the use of the natural environment, and justice for all and the illumination of pressing social problems.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/a-place-at-the-table] As of October 2015, it has a 90% approval ratings from 61 professional reviews aggregated by Rotten Tomatoes.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] His companies attracted controversy during the 1991 Beef Tribunal, while a burger manufacturing facility, Silvercrest, was one of a number of high-profile food manufacturing facilities which were involved in the 2013 European horse meat scandal.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] An investigation by the Irish Government into the issue concluded that the company had never knowingly purchased meat containing equine DNA.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] Goodman was born in County Louth in the east of Ireland.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] He attended St Mary's College, Dundalk, but left school without finishing his Intermediate Certificate, and followed his father into the meat industry, starting with meat by-products and sheep.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] He was "born to a well-off family who had been in the meat business for six generations".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] He lives with his wife Kitty at Castlebellingham, County Louth.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] His brother Peter Goodman, who had worked as deputy chairman of Goodman International (now deceased), fell out with Larry; they hadn't talked in years prior to his death.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] Larry owed Peter a large amount of money at the time of his death and refused to pay his widow what was rightly owed.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] His other brother Michael was a farmer in County Louth.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] They are no longer talking to one another.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] In the late 1960s Goodman bought Anglo-Irish Meats in Dundalk, which put him into the processing industry in a substantial way.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] He then began exporting, building up contacts in the Middle East in particular.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] He sold meat to Libya, Iran, Iraq and Egypt – often going himself as salesman.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] He was on the advisory committee for HSBC's opening of operations in Ireland in 1979, along with Dermot Nolan, Michael Carvill and Peter Hutson.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] In April 1980, Anglo Irish Meat Group purchased a meat plant at Bagenalstown, County Carlow, from Meade-Lonsdale for around £2.2m.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] In June 1980 it was announced that Goodman would invest £10m for a new meat plant in Ardee, County Louth, employing 360 people "when it reaches full production".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] It also announced an additional £10m investment to expand operations at Cahir, Nenagh and Bagenalstown.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] In October 1980, Goodman bought Fermanagh Meats in Enniskillen for about £1.5m.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] The plant employed 60 people and processed about 1,000 head of cattle a week.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] By this time Goodman's meat empire was turning over about £100m a year.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] In July 1981 it was announced that the IDA would put £2m towards the £9m expansion of Goodman's plants.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] One of his companies, Irish Agricultural Feed Co also built a feed manufacturing facility at Castlebellingham, and a complex to "over-winter up to 15,000 cattle to boost supplies to the factories at a time when few cattle are finished for slaughter".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] The complex "was the result of 14 years research" and cost £2m.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] By this time Anglo Irish Group employed some 700 people and turnover had reached £120m per year.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] In January 1982 it was announced that Anglo Irish Beef Group had won a £25.5m contract to supply beef to Iraq.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] The contract involved supplying 9,000 tonnes of boneless consumer cuts and frozen bone-in meat and was part of an overall order for 54,000 tonnes of beef placed by Iraq.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] In March 1983, AIBG acquired the four Northern Ireland factories of the animal by-products processors Robert Wilson for around £1m.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] By this stage AIBP was slaughtering more than 250,000 cattle a year, and 10,000 cattle were being fattened at Goodman's feeding lots in Louth.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] Later that year, in April 1983, he won contracts to supply $50m worth of fresh frozen beef to Iran and Morocco.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] At the time of the deal, Goodman complained that because there was no Variable Premium subsidy scheme in the UK, exporters there had an effective subsidy of $300 a tonne on beef exporters, thus enabling them to undercut Irish exporters.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] In September 1983 Goodman won a $33m contract to supply beef to Iran.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] Goodman praised then Minister for Agriculture Austin Deasy, whose visit to Tehran "greatly facilitated the securing of the new contract".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] In December 1984 AIBP purchased the entire fresh meat division of Dalgety PLC, a publicly quoted UK group.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] It included facilities in York, Blisworth, Wellingborough and Reading, as well as distribution depots in Jersey and Berkshire.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] By this time turnover at Goodman had reached £300m a year.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] The purchased was followed by the acquisition of the Waterford plant of Clover Meats (after that company's collapse) for around £2m in February 1985.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] It includes the purchase of National Proteins, a by-products plant processing meat and bone meal from edible offal.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] On 9 March 1989, TDs Barry Desmond and Tomás Mac Giolla made a series of allegations about Goodman International in the Dáil.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] Desmond indicated that the media had been subject to writs, and called for a tribunal of inquiry into the Goodman Group.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] In a March 1989 *Irish Times* story, Goodman International denied the allegations made by Desmond and Mac Giolla.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] Goodman said it was shocked by the allegations made and that they were "false and malicious comments".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] "The use of the privilege of the Dail to further this campaign against an Irish company is a matter of the gravest concern," the statement read.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] On 2 August 1990, Saddam Hussein ordered his troops to enter and occupy Kuwait.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] Initially the losses to the Goodman group and its bankers were estimated at £70m.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] By this time Goodman's companies accounted for 40% of the national beef kill, and had turnover in the region of £1 billion, almost all of it in exports.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] On 24 August 1990, share prices on the Irish Stock Exchange fell by £400m, with some of Goodman's companies including Food Industries (in which he held a 68% stake) falling from 170p to 110p.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] By Friday, 24 August 1990 Taoiseach Charles Haughey recalled the Dáil for an emergency session to pass a section of the Companies Bill on Tuesday, 28 August.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] Haughey denied that the legislation was being enacted specifically to aid Goodman.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] The legislation allowed for the courts to appoint an examiner who could freeze company assets for up to 12 months – compared at the time to US Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection laws.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] It later emerged that Goodman International was owed up to £180 million by Iraq and that the group owed over £400m to banks around the world – and that the group was "insolvent to the tune of somewhat under £100m".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] As the group holding company, Goodman International, was an unlimited company and Goodman was 98% owner, he could personally be called on to make good any shortfall owing to creditors.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] On 13 May 1991 Granada Television broadcast an episode of the investigative programme, *World in Action* with Susan O'Keeffe.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] The show examined the core business of Goodman International, how its operations were funded by national and European Community schemes, including export insurance and credit schemes, EC export subsidies and the variable premium paid on cattle.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] It claimed that the dominant position of Goodman in the Irish and British beef processing industry may not be in the best interests of consumers.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] It also made allegations of inappropriate political influence by Goodman.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] The programme featured Patrick McGuinness, a former Goodman accountant who had left the company and immigrated to Canada.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] The next day Opposition parties called for a full judicial inquiry into the allegations made on the programme.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] Goodman said he would welcome any investigation from any source and that he would co-operate fully with it.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] He said he was astounded by the allegations made in the programme.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] He said that the malpractices alleged during the programme in relation to stamping and weighing meat had never been carried out in a "routine fashion", and if they had taken place they had done so without his knowledge or consent.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] He said systems that meant payment of £3 million in non-taxable wages to employees had existed but that this had been ended.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] The Tribunal of Inquiry into the Beef Processing Industry, also known as the Beef Tribunal, was established on 31 May 1991, chaired by Justice Liam Hamilton.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] The Tribunal began hearings on 21 June 1991 and it reported its conclusions in July 1994, at the time the Irish State's longest running inquiry.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] The Tribunal was established by the then Fianna Fáil/Progressive Democrat coalition, though only after the leader of the PDs, Des O'Malley threatened to pull out of the coalition if no inquiry was established.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/abp-food-group] Then Taoiseach Charles Haughey acquiesced to the demand.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/advertising-standards-authority-for-ireland] The **Advertising Standards Authority** (**ASA**), previously known as the Advertising Standards Authority for Ireland, is the self-regulatory organisation (SRO) for advertising industry in Ireland.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/advertising-standards-authority-for-ireland] The 7th edition of its Code was introduced with effect from March 2016.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/advertising-standards-authority-for-ireland] In October 2023, the Advertising Standards Authority and the Competition and Consumer Protection Commission (CCPC) issued fresh guidance for Irish Influencers on the clear labelling of ads on social media.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/advertising-standards-authority-for-ireland] The Advertising Standards Authority was established in 1981 and substantially restructured in 1988 at the request of the Director of Consumer Affairs, to place the complaints handling at arm's length from the industry representation.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/advertising-standards-authority-for-ireland] In 2018, the Advertising Standards Authority for the first time upheld a complaint against a blogger, for consumer-generated advertising of makeup using retouched photographs of herself.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/advertising-standards-authority-for-ireland] In March 2024, ASA underwent a brand refresh which included a new name, visual identity and website.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Al Jazeera is known for its in-depth and frontline reporting particularly in conflict zones such as the Arab Spring, the Gaza–Israel conflict and others.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Al Jazeera's coverage of the Arab Spring won the network numerous awards, including the Peabody Award.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] It positions itself as an alternative media platform to the dominance of Western media outlets like CNN and BBC, focusing on narrative reporting where subjects present their own stories.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] The channel launched on 15 November 2006 with an investment of approximately $1 billion from the Qatari government.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Initially slated to be named Al Jazeera International, the channel was renamed nine months prior to the launch.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] This decision was influenced by one of the channel's backers, who argued that the original Arabic-language channel already encompassed an international scope.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] The channel was expected to reach approximately 40 million households, but it significantly surpassed this launch target, reaching 80 million homes.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] By 2009, the service was accessible in every major European market and available to 130 million homes across more than 100 countries through cable and satellite, according to a network spokeswoman in Washington.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] However, the channel had limited penetration in the American market, where it was carried by only one satellite service and a handful of cable networks.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Al Jazeera English subsequently launched a campaign to enter the North American market, including a dedicated website.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] In August 2011, it became available to some cable subscribers in New York, having previously been an option for some viewers in Washington, D.C., Ohio, and Los Angeles.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] The channel primarily reached the United States through its live online streaming service.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Following approval from the Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission on 26 November 2009, Al Jazeera English became readily available on most major Canadian television providers, including Rogers and Bell Satellite TV.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Al Jazeera English and Iran's state-run Press TV were the only international English-language television broadcasters with journalists reporting from inside both Gaza and Israel during the 2008–2009 Israel-Gaza conflict.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Foreign press access to Gaza was limited via either Egypt or Israel.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] However, Al Jazeera's reporters Ayman Mohyeldin and Sherine Tadros were already inside Gaza when the conflict began.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] The network encourages online viewing at its own website or via its channel on YouTube.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Al Jazeera English HD launched in the United Kingdom on Freeview on 26 November 2013, and began streaming in HD on YouTube in 2015.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] On 1 January 2020, Al Jazeera English debuted a new graphics package to coincide with the renovation of its main Doha studio, the last of the channel's three main studios (Doha, London, and Washington D.C.) to be upgraded since the channel's launch in 2006.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] On 3 January 2013, Al Jazeera Media Network announced that it had purchased Current TV in the United States and would launch an American news channel.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Sixty percent of the channel's programming would be produced in the United States, while 40% would be from Al Jazeera English.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] This was later changed at the request of pay-television providers to almost 100% US programming.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] However, Al Jazeera America maintained a close working relationship with Al Jazeera English.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] The channel aired *Newshour* in the morning and midday hours, and cut to live Al Jazeera English coverage of large breaking international news stories outside those hours.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] The Al Jazeera English programmes *Witness*, *Earthrise*, *The Listening Post*, *Talk To Al Jazeera*, *Al Jazeera Correspondent* and *101 East* along with *Al Jazeera Investigates* aired regularly on Al Jazeera America.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] On 13 January 2016, Al Jazeera America announced that the network would shut down on 12 April 2016, citing the "economic landscape".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] In 2013, Al Jazeera Media Network began planning a new channel called *Al Jazeera UK*; the British channel was set to broadcast for five hours during prime time as a local opt-out of Al Jazeera English.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Ultimately, the planned UK channel never materialised.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Al Jazeera English continued to broadcast some of its daily bulletins from London until July 2023, when it moved its base to Qatar.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] The channel is available in many countries, mostly via satellite, sometimes via cable.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Al Jazeera English provides a free HD stream on its website for unlimited viewing.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Al Jazeera news segments were frequently included on the American public television program Worldfocus which aired from 6 October 2008 until 2 April 2010.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Al Jazeera can also be streamed on any iOS or Android device with an internet connection using a free application.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Al Jazeera English is also available on connected TV and OTT streaming services like Pluto TV and Haystack News.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Along with a free unlimited high-quality stream on the official Al Jazeera English website, Online subscriptions allowing unlimited viewing may be purchased from Jump TV, RealPlayer, and VDC.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Headlines from Al Jazeera English are available on Twitter.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Al Jazeera English's website also contains news reports and full episodes of their programs that can be viewed for free on their website.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] The videos are hosted by YouTube, where viewers can also go to find the videos.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Al Jazeera English is available in the UK and Ireland on Freeview channel 235, Sky channel 511, Freesat channel 203 and Virgin Media channel 622.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] A notice appearing on Freeview channel 235 indicates that Al Jazeera is scheduled to end there on 30 September 2024 but that its service will remain on channel 251 as a streaming service for STBs that support streaming.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] The channel initially began test streaming Al Jazeera English (then called "Al Jazeera International") in March 2006 on Hot Bird, Astra 1E, Hispasat, AsiaSat3S, Eutelsat 28A and Panamsat PAS 10.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Telenors Thor, Türksat and Eutelsat 25A were added to the satellites carrying it.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Eutelsat 28A carried the test stream on frequency 11.681 under the name "AJI".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Al Jazeera English is available in Sub-Saharan Africa mainly via DStv and StarTimes' satellite and terrestrial TV platforms.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] It is also available FTA on satellites like Belintersat 51.5°E and Nilesat 201.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] In Northern Africa, Al Jazeera English is available on telcos like Etisalat.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] It is also available via satellite, on Badr°26E and various local cable operators.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] In New Zealand, Al Jazeera English is available 24 hours a day on Freeview (New Zealand) channel 16 and Sky (New Zealand) channel 90.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] From October 2013, Freeview (New Zealand) broadcast on the Kordia operated free-to-air DVB-T terrestrial network.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Prior to the December 2012 analog switchoff Triangle TV re-broadcast various Al Jazeera programmes in Auckland on its free-to-air UHF channel.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] TV One was going to replace BBC World News with this service during their off-air hours of 01:30 to 06:00 from 1 April 2013, however opted to run infomercials instead.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] In April 2010, Al Jazeera English was taken off air in Singapore Singtel TV with unspecified reasons, according to the official Al Jazeera English website.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] On 7 December 2010, Al Jazeera said its English language service has got a downlink license to broadcast in India.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Satellite and cable companies would therefore be allowed to broadcast Al Jazeera in the country.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] The channel launched on Dish TV in November 2011, and is considering a Hindi-language channel.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Tata Play satellite service broadcasts this on Channel 637 (SD) in India.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] On 26 November 2009, the Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission approved "a request to add Al Jazeera English (AJE) to the lists of eligible satellite services for distribution on a digital basis and amends the lists of eligible satellite services accordingly".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Al Jazeera English became available on Rogers Cable, Videotron and Bell Satellite TV on 4 May 2010.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Al Jazeera English is available via satellite across all of North America free to air via Globecast on Galaxy 19 on the Ku band in DVB format.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] As of 2011, only a small number of Americans were able to watch the channel on their televisions.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Among the markets where it was available were Bristol County, Rhode Island, Toledo and Sandusky, Ohio, Burlington, Vermont, Houston, Texas, and Washington, DC.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Industry giant Comcast originally planned to carry Al Jazeera English in 2007, but reversed its decision shortly before the channel's launch, citing "the already-saturated television market".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] The two major American satellite providers, DirecTV and Dish Network, had similar plans but also changed their minds, with speculation that the decision may have been influenced by allegations by the Bush administration of "anti-American bias" on the channel.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] With Al Jazeera's coverage of the Egyptian Revolution of 2011, the channel drew acclaim and received renewed attention.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] *The New York Times* reported on 1 February 2011 that 1.6 million U.S. viewers had tuned in via Internet stream, and stated that new discussions were underway with carriers.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] The following month, it was announced that Al Jazeera entered carriage negotiations with Comcast and Time Warner Cable.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Salon.com described the channel's English-language coverage as "mandatory viewing for anyone interested in the world-changing events currently happening in Egypt", while *Huffington Post* contributor Jeff Jarvis claimed it was "un-American" for operators to not carry the network.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] When Al Jazeera covered the Libyan Civil War, U.S.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Secretary of State Hillary Clinton noted an increasing American audience for the network, saying that "viewership of Al Jazeera is going up in the United States because it's real news.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] On 1 February 2011, Internet appliance Roku posted on its Facebook page that the English-language Al Jazeera Live would be streaming on Roku devices through a private channel called Newscaster and also through the BBC channel.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] It permitted the announcement following unrest in Egypt so American viewers can watch the latest events going on in the Middle East.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] A Roku user must add the private channel Newscaster from the Roku website.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] On 1 August 2011, Al Jazeera English began airing 23 hours a day in New York City as part of a sublet agreement with cable channel RISE, a former Spanish-language network, which is carried on WRNN-TV's DT2 subchannel (the other hours were used to meet FCC E/I and local programming guidelines).
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] The network aired on Time Warner Cable on channel 92 and on Verizon FiOS on channel 481.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] On 2 January 2013, Al Jazeera announced that it had acquired the U.S.-based cable TV channel Current TV for a reported $500 million.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] With this acquisition, Al Jazeera launched a new channel, called Al Jazeera America, with a heavy dose of U.S. domestic news along with Al Jazeera English programming and news, to an estimated 40 million U.S. households—putting it in direct competition with CNN, MSNBC and Fox News Channel.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Due to contracts with U.S. cable and satellite carriers for Al Jazeera America the official Al Jazeera English live stream was geo-blocked in the United States on 18 August 2013.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] With the launch of Al Jazeera America, Al Jazeera English was excluded from all US services carrying or providing the channel, including YouTube, with Al Jazeera America material replacing all Al Jazeera English video content and live streams.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Most Al Jazeera English video content was no longer officially available in the United States.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] In April 2014 the Al Jazeera English show *Empire* was not geo-blocked in the United States.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Shortly after the programs *Indian Hospital*, *Viewfinder*, *Lifelines: The Quest for Global Health* and *Head to Head* were available also.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] These programs were the only AJE shows officially non-geoblocked for American viewing during the time that Al Jazeera America was in existence.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] With the closure of Al Jazeera America in April 2016 it was expected that the official live stream of Al Jazeera English and access to its programmes would eventually be restored to the United States.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] The online live stream of Al Jazeera English was made available to viewers in the United States once again in September 2016.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Shortly after launching in 2003, Al Jazeera's English website was hit by hackers who launched denial-of-service attacks.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Aljazeera.com has served as the primary web address for both the Al Jazeera English and former Al Jazeera America websites since early 2011.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] The domain name was acquired by Al Jazeera Media Network from Aljazeera Publishing, a Dubai-based media company which previously used the domain as the website for their unrelated publication Aljazeera Magazine.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] This followed after a long-running domain name dispute between the two entities, which included a failed 2005 attempt by Al Jazeera Network to take control of the domain.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Confusion between the two entities resulted in some articles from Al Jazeera magazine being erroneously attributed to the Al Jazeera Network.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] In 2012, 40 percent of the 150 million visits Al Jazeera English's website received originated from the United States.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] The Al Jazeera Investigative Unit is a specialized investigative journalism team within Al Jazeera.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] The unit is known for producing investigative reports and documentaries on a wide range of global issues, including politics, human rights, corruption, environmental issues, and more.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] The documentaries are featured as exclusive specials within their dedicated series Al Jazeera Investigates.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] On 29 December 2013, Egyptian security forces arrested three Al Jazeera English journalists—Australian Peter Greste, Canadian Mohamed Fahmy, and Egyptian Baher Mohamed—at Cairo's Marriott Hotel, accusing them of reporting news damaging to national security.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Despite international outcry and campaigns like #FreeAJStaff, calls for their release from the UN, EU, and the US went unheeded.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] The journalists faced a series of trial delays, with questionable evidence, including misleading videos, inaudible audio recordings, and unrelated images.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] On 23 June 2014, Greste and Fahmy received seven-year sentences, while Mohamed was sentenced to 10 years.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] The verdict was widely criticized, with global leaders and media outlets denouncing it as a politically motivated attack on press freedom.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Calls for amnesty were rebuffed by Egypt, asserting the independence of its justice system.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Amid mounting pressure, Greste was released and deported to Australia on 1 February 2015.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] On 29 August 2015, the trio faced an additional three-year sentence, sparking international condemnation.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] The Canadian government sought Fahmy's pardon and deportation, which was granted on 23 September 2015, alongside a pardon for Mohamed, as part of a larger pardon by Egyptian President el-Sisi for 100 individuals.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] The case underscored concerns about press freedom and raised calls for reevaluating foreign aid to Egypt.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] In 2012, Melissa Chan, who served as the longstanding China correspondent for Al Jazeera English, faced expulsion from the country.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Although the Chinese government refrained from publicly disclosing the reasons for her expulsion, it was widely understood that their dissatisfaction stemmed from a documentary aired by the channel that focused on China's prison system.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] The incident prompted inquiries during the Beijing press corps' routine questioning at the Chinese Foreign Ministry's daily press briefing on 8 May 2012.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] However, officials provided no explanation and selectively omitted most related questions when publishing the official transcript.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Following her expulsion, Melissa Chan continued her journalistic career at Al Jazeera America.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Emmy Award-winning journalist Dave Marash resigned from his position in March 2008, saying his exit was due in part to an anti-American bias at the network, which is little seen in the US.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Marash said he felt that attitude more from British administrators than Arabs.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] He said there were other reasons for his exit and was proud of the network's coverage of issues south of the equator, but that he ultimately felt that it was not the right place for him.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] On 12 October 2008, Al Jazeera English broadcast interviews with people attending a Sarah Palin United States presidential election rally in St.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Clairsville, Ohio, with interviewees making comments about Barack Obama such as "he regards white people as trash" and "I'm afraid if he wins, the blacks will take over"...The report received over two million views on YouTube.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Al-Jazeera, once viewed skeptically in the U.S, received broad praise for its Egypt coverage, which boosted its American audience and renewed calls for its inclusion on U.S. cable networks.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Additional programming geared towards an American audience includes a day's worth of special coverage marking the 10th anniversary of the terrorist attacks of 11 September 2001.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] Al Jazeera has also launched *The Stream*, a show based in Washington D.C. that discusses social media, which targets an American audience.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/aljazeera-com] On 2 January 2013, Al Jazeera purchased the American channel Current TV and rebranded as Al Jazeera America in August 2013.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] There are various ways in which antisemitism is manifested, ranging in the level of severity of Jewish persecution.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] On the more subtle end, it consists of expressions of hatred or discrimination against individual Jews and may or may not be accompanied by violence.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] At the extreme, it consists of pogroms or genocide, which may or may not be state-sponsored.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Although the term *antisemitism* did not come into common usage until the 19th century, it is also applied to previous and later anti-Jewish incidents.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Historically, most of the world's violent antisemitic events have taken place in Europe, where modern antisemitism began to emerge from antisemitism in Christian communities during the Middle Ages.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Since the early 20th century, there has been a sharp rise in antisemitic incidents across the Arab world, largely due to the advent of Arab antisemitic conspiracy theories, which were influenced by European antisemitic conspiracy theories.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Beginning in 1879, the compound word *Antisemitismus* was first used in print in Germany as a "scientific-sounding term" for *Judenhass* (lit.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] 'Jew-hatred'), and it has since been used to refer to anti-Jewish sentiment alone.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] In the 21st century, the idea that there is a variation of antisemitism known as "new antisemitism" has been discussed.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] According to this view, since Israel is a Jewish state, expressions of anti-Zionist positions could harbour antisemitic sentiments, and criticism of Israel can serve as a vehicle for attacks against Jews in general.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] First used in the 1770s by members of the Göttingen school of history, the coining of "Semites" as biblical terminology for race was derived from *Shem* (שֵׁם), the name of one of the three sons of Noah in the Book of Genesis, together with the parallel terms *Hamites* and *Japhetites*.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] The origin of "antisemitic" terminologies is found in the responses of Orientalist Moritz Steinschneider to the views of Orientalist Ernest Renan.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Steinschneider used this phrase to characterise the French philosopher Ernest Renan's false ideas about how 'Semitic races' were inferior to 'Aryan races'".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Pseudoscientific theories concerning race, civilization, and "progress" had become quite widespread in Europe in the second half of the 19th century, especially as Prussian nationalistic historian Heinrich von Treitschke did much to promote this form of racism.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] He coined the phrase "the Jews are our misfortune", which would later be widely used by Nazis.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] According to Falk, Treitschke uses the term "Semitic" almost synonymously with "Jewish", in contrast to Renan's use of it to refer to a whole range of peoples, based generally on linguistic criteria.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Hess, the term was originally used by its authors to "stress the radical difference between their own 'antisemitism' and earlier forms of antagonism toward Jews and Judaism".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] In 1879, German journalist Wilhelm Marr published a pamphlet, *Der Sieg des Judenthums über das Germanenthum.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Vom nicht confessionellen Standpunkt aus betrachtet* (*The Victory of the Jewish Spirit over the Germanic Spirit.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Observed from a non-religious perspective*), in which he used the word *Semitismus* interchangeably with the word *Judentum* to denote both "Jewry" (the Jews as a collective) and "Jewishness" (the quality of being Jewish, or the Jewish spirit).
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] He accused the Jews of a worldwide conspiracy against non-Jews, called for resistance against "this foreign power", and claimed that "there will not be a single office in the land, including the highest, which will not have been usurped by the Jews".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] This followed his 1862 book *Der Judenspiegel* (*A Mirror to the Jews*), in which he argued that "Judaism must cease to exist if humanity is to commence", demanding that Judaism be both dissolved as a "religious-denominational sect" and subject to criticism "as a race, a civil and social entity".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] This use of *Semitismus* was followed by a coining of *Antisemitismus*, which was used to indicate opposition to the Jews as a people and opposition to the Jewish spirit, which Marr interpreted as infiltrating German culture.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] The pamphlet became very popular, and in the same year Marr founded the *Antisemiten-Liga* ('League of Antisemites'), apparently named to follow the *Anti-Kanzler-Liga* ('Anti-Chancellor League').
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] The league was the first German organisation committed specifically to combating the alleged threat to Germany and German culture posed by the Jews and their influence and advocating their forced removal from the country.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] So far as can be ascertained, the word was first widely printed in 1881, when Marr published *Zwanglose Antisemitische Hefte*, and Wilhelm Scherer used the term *Antisemiten* in the January issue of *Neue Freie Presse*.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] The *Jewish Encyclopedia* reports, "In February 1881, a correspondent of the *Allgemeine Zeitung des Judentums* speaks of 'Anti-Semitism' as a designation which recently came into use ('Allg.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] The word *antisemitism* was borrowed into English from German in 1881.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] *Oxford English Dictionary* editor James Murray wrote that it was not included in the first edition because "*Anti-Semite* and its family were then probably very new in English use, and not thought likely to be more than passing nonce-words...
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Would that anti-Semitism had had no more than a fleeting interest!" The related term *philosemitism* was used by 1881.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] From the outset the term *anti-Semitism* bore special racial connotations and meant specifically prejudice against Jews.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] The word *Semitic* was coined for use in linguistics by German Orientalist August Ludwig von Schlözer in 1781 to designate the Semitic group of languages—Aramaic, Arabic, Hebrew and others—allegedly spoken by the descendants of the Biblical figure Shem, son of Noah.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Though the general definition of *antisemitism* is 'hostility or prejudice against Jews', and, according to Olaf Blaschke, the word has become an "umbrella term for negative stereotypes about Jews", a number of authorities have developed more formal definitions.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Elaborating on Fein's definition, Dietz Bering of the University of Cologne writes that, to antisemites, "Jews are not only partially but totally bad by nature, that is, their bad traits are incorrigible.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Because of this bad nature: (1) Jews have to be seen not as individuals but as a collective.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] (2) Jews remain essentially alien in the surrounding societies.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] For Swiss historian Sonja Weinberg, as distinct from economic and religious anti-Judaism, antisemitism in its specifically modern form shows conceptual innovation, a resort to "science" to defend itself, new functional forms, and organisational differences.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] It was anti-liberal, racialist and nationalist.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] It promoted the myth that Jews conspired to 'judaise' the world; it served to consolidate social identity; it channeled dissatisfactions among victims of the capitalist system; and it was used as a conservative cultural code to fight emancipation and liberalism.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] In 2003, Israeli politician Natan Sharansky developed what he called the "three D" test to distinguish antisemitism from criticism of Israel, giving Delegitimization, Demonization, and Double standards as a litmus test for the former.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] British-American historian Bernard Lewis, writing in 2006, defined antisemitism as a special case of prejudice, hatred, or persecution directed against people who are in some way different from the rest.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] According to Lewis, antisemitism is marked by two distinct features: Jews are judged according to a standard different from that applied to others, and they are accused of "cosmic evil".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Thus, "it is perfectly possible to hate and even to persecute Jews without necessarily being anti-Semitic" unless this hatred or persecution displays one of the two features specific to antisemitism.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] There have been a number of efforts by international and governmental bodies to define antisemitism formally.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] In 2005, the European Monitoring Centre on Racism and Xenophobia (EUMC, now the Fundamental Rights Agency), an agency of the European Union, developed a more detailed working definition, which stated: "Antisemitism is a certain perception of Jews, which may be expressed as hatred toward Jews.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] The EUMC working definition was adopted by the European Parliament Working Group on Antisemitism in 2010, by the United States Department of State in 2017, in the Operational Hate Crime Guidance of the UK College of Policing in 2014 and by the UK's Campaign Against Antisemitism.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] In 2016, the working definition was adopted by the International Holocaust Remembrance Alliance.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] IHRA's Working definition of antisemitism is among the most controversial documents related to opposition to antisemitism, and critics argue that it has been used to censor criticism of Israel.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] In response to the perceived lack of clarity in the IHRA definition, two new definitions of antisemitism were published in 2021, the Nexus Document in February 2021 and the Jerusalem Declaration on Antisemitism in March 2021.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] In 1879, Wilhelm Marr founded the Antisemiten-Liga (Anti-Semitic League).
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Identification with antisemitism and as an antisemite was politically advantageous in Europe during the late 19th century.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] For example, Karl Lueger, the popular mayor of fin de siècle Vienna, skillfully exploited antisemitism as a way of channeling public discontent to his political advantage.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] In its 1910 obituary of Lueger, *The New York Times* notes that Lueger was "Chairman of the Christian Social Union of the Parliament and of the Anti-Semitic Union of the Diet of Lower Austria.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Cuza organized the *Alianța Antisemită* and the *Liga Antisemită Universală* in Bucharest.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] In the period before World War II, when animosity towards Jews was far more commonplace, it was not uncommon for a person, an organization, or a political party to self-identify as an antisemite or antisemitic.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] The early Zionist pioneer Leon Pinsker, a professional physician, preferred the clinical-sounding term ***Judeophobia*** (also ***Judaeophobia***) to antisemitism, which he regarded as a misnomer.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] The word *Judeophobia* first appeared in his pamphlet *Auto-Emancipation*, published anonymously in German in September 1882, where it was described as an irrational fear or hatred of Jews.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] According to Pinsker, this irrational fear was an inherited predisposition.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] In the aftermath of the Kristallnacht pogrom in 1938, German propaganda minister Goebbels announced: "The German people is anti-Semitic.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] After 1945 victory of the Allies over Nazi Germany, and particularly after the full extent of the Nazi genocide against the Jews became known, the term *antisemitism* acquired pejorative connotations.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] This marked a full circle shift in usage, from an era just decades earlier when "Jew" was used as a pejorative term.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Yehuda Bauer wrote in 1984: "There are no anti-Semites in the world ...
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Nobody says, 'I am anti-Semitic.' You cannot, after Hitler.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] The term has been described as confusing, for in modern usage *Semitic* designates a language group, not a race.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] In this sense, the term is a misnomer, since there are many speakers of Semitic languages (e.g., Arabs, Ethiopians, and Assyrians) who are not the objects of antisemitic prejudices, while there are many Jews who do not speak Hebrew, a Semitic language.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Though *antisemitism* could be construed as prejudice against people who speak Semitic languages, this is not how the term is commonly used.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] The term may be spelled with or without a hyphen (*antisemitism* or *anti-Semitism*).
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Many scholars and institutions favor the unhyphenated form.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] According to Carroll, who first cites O'Hare and Bauer on "the existence of something called 'Semitism'", "the hyphenated word thus reflects the bipolarity that is at the heart of the problem of antisemitism".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Hess identified the operative referent in the original usage to have been "antisemit[e]".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] The Associated Press and its accompanying *AP Stylebook* adopted the unhyphenated spelling in 2021.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Style guides for the *New York Times* and *Wall Street Journal* later adopted this spelling as well.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] It has also been adopted by many Holocaust museums, such as the United States Holocaust Memorial Museum and Yad Vashem.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] The study of antisemitism has become politically controversial because of differing interpretations of the Holocaust and the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] There are two competing views of antisemitism—eternalism and contextualism.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] The eternalist view sees antisemitism as separate from other forms of racism and prejudice and an exceptionalist, transhistorical force teleologically culminating in the Holocaust.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Most Zionists do not believe that antisemitism can be combatted with education or other means.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] The contextual approach treats antisemitism as a type of racism and focuses on the historical context in which hatred of Jews emerges.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Some contextualists restrict the use of "antisemitism" to refer exclusively to the era of modern racism, treating anti-Judaism as a separate phenomenon.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Historian David Engel has challenged the project to define antisemitism, arguing that it essentializes Jewish history as one of persecution and discrimination.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Engel argues that the term "antisemitism" is not useful in historical analysis because it implies that there are links between anti-Jewish prejudices expressed in different contexts, without evidence of such a connection.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Antisemitism manifests itself in a variety of ways.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] René König mentions social antisemitism, economic antisemitism, religious antisemitism, and political antisemitism as examples.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] These difficulties may contribute to the existence of different taxonomies that have been developed to categorize the forms of antisemitism.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] The forms identified are substantially the same; it is primarily the number of forms and their definitions that differ.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Bernard Lazare, writing in the 1890s, identified three forms of antisemitism: Christian antisemitism, economic antisemitism, and ethnologic antisemitism.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] William Brustein names four categories: religious, racial, economic, and political.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Louis Harap, writing in the 1980s, separated "economic antisemitism" and merges "political" and "nationalistic" antisemitism into "ideological antisemitism".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Harap also adds a category of "social antisemitism".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Religious antisemitism, also known as anti-Judaism, is antipathy towards Jews because of their perceived religious beliefs.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] In theory, antisemitism and attacks against individual Jews would stop if Jews stopped practicing Judaism or changed their public faith, especially by conversion to the official or right religion.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] However, in some cases, discrimination continues after conversion, as in the case of *marranos* (Christianized Jews in Spain and Portugal) in the late 15th century and 16th century, who were suspected of secretly practising Judaism or Jewish customs.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Although the origins of antisemitism are rooted in the Judeo-Christian conflict, other forms of antisemitism have developed in modern times.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Drumont founded the Antisemitic League of France.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] The underlying premise of economic antisemitism is that Jews perform harmful economic activities or that economic activities become harmful when they are performed by Jews.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Linking Jews and money underpins the most damaging and lasting antisemitic canards.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Antisemites claim that Jews control the world finances, a theory promoted in the fraudulent *The Protocols of the Elders of Zion* and later repeated by Henry Ford and his *The Dearborn Independent*.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] In the modern era, such myths continue to be spread in books such as *The Secret Relationship Between Blacks and Jews* published by the Nation of Islam and on the internet.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Gerald Krefetz summarizes the myth as "[Jews] control the banks, the money supply, the economy, and businesses—of the community, of the country, of the world".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Krefetz gives, as illustrations, many slurs and proverbs (in several different languages) which suggest that Jews are stingy, or greedy, or miserly, or aggressive bargainers.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] During the nineteenth century, Jews were described as "scurrilous, stupid, and tight-fisted", but after the Jewish Emancipation and the rise of Jews to the middle- or upper-class in Europe were portrayed as "clever, devious, and manipulative financiers out to dominate [world finances]".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Léon Poliakov asserts that economic antisemitism is not a distinct form of antisemitism, but merely a manifestation of theologic antisemitism (because, without the theological causes of economic antisemitism, there would be no economic antisemitism).
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] In opposition to this view, Derek Penslar contends that in the modern era, economic antisemitism is "distinct and nearly constant" but theological antisemitism is "often subdued".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] An academic study by Francesco D'Acunto, Marcel Prokopczuk, and Michael Weber showed that people who live in areas of Germany that contain the most brutal history of antisemitic persecution are more likely to be distrustful of finance in general.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Therefore, they tended to invest less money in the stock market and make poor financial decisions.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Racial antisemitism is prejudice against Jews as a racial/ethnic group, rather than Judaism as a religion.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Racial antisemitism is the idea that the Jews are a distinct and inferior race compared to their host nations.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] In the late 19th century and early 20th century, it gained mainstream acceptance as part of the eugenics movement, which categorized non-Europeans as inferior.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] It more specifically claimed that Northern Europeans, or "Aryans", were superior.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Racial antisemites saw the Jews as part of a Semitic race and emphasized their non-European origins and culture.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] They saw Jews as beyond redemption even if they converted to the majority religion.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Racial antisemitism replaced the hatred of Judaism with the hatred of Jews as a group.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] In the context of the Industrial Revolution, following the Jewish Emancipation, Jews rapidly urbanized and experienced a period of greater social mobility.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] With the decreasing role of religion in public life tempering religious antisemitism, a combination of growing nationalism, the rise of eugenics, and resentment at the socio-economic success of the Jews led to the newer, and more virulent, racist antisemitism.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] In the early 19th century, a number of laws enabling the emancipation of the Jews were enacted in Western European countries.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] The old laws restricting them to ghettos, as well as the many laws that limited their property rights, rights of worship and occupation, were rescinded.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Despite this, traditional discrimination and hostility to Jews on religious grounds persisted and was supplemented by racial antisemitism, encouraged by the work of racial theorists such as Joseph Arthur de Gobineau and particularly his *Essay on the Inequality of the Human Race* of 1853–1855.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Nationalist agendas based on ethnicity, known as ethnonationalism, usually excluded the Jews from the national community as an alien race.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Allied to this were theories of Social Darwinism, which stressed a putative conflict between higher and lower races of human beings.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Such theories, usually posited by northern Europeans, advocated the superiority of white Aryans to Semitic Jews.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] William Brustein defines political antisemitism as hostility toward Jews based on the belief that Jews seek national or world power.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Yisrael Gutman characterizes political antisemitism as tending to "lay responsibility on the Jews for defeats and political economic crises" while seeking to "exploit opposition and resistance to Jewish influence as elements in political party platforms." Derek J.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] According to Viktor Karády, political antisemitism became widespread after the legal emancipation of the Jews and sought to reverse some of the consequences of that emancipation.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Holocaust denial and Jewish conspiracy theories are also considered forms of antisemitism.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Zoological conspiracy theories have been propagated by Arab media and Arabic language websites, alleging a "Zionist plot" behind the use of animals to attack civilians or to conduct espionage.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] In this view, the proponents of the new concept believe that criticisms of Israel and Zionism are often disproportionate in degree and unique in kind, and they attribute this to antisemitism.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Jewish scholar Gustavo Perednik posited in 2004 that anti-Zionism in itself represents a form of discrimination against Jews, in that it singles out Jewish national aspirations as an illegitimate and racist endeavor, and "proposes actions that would result in the death of millions of Jews".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p01] Proponents of this theory assert that the new antisemitism deploys traditional antisemitic motifs, including older motifs such as the blood libel.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Many authors see the roots of modern antisemitism in both pagan antiquity and early Christianity.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] The first clear examples of anti-Jewish sentiment can be traced to the 3rd century BCE to Alexandria, the home to the largest Jewish diaspora community in the world at the time and where the Septuagint, a Greek translation of the Hebrew Bible, was produced.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Manetho, an Egyptian priest and historian of that era, wrote scathingly of the Jews.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] His themes are repeated in the works of Chaeremon, Lysimachus, Poseidonius, Apollonius Molon, and in Apion and Tacitus.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Agatharchides of Cnidus ridiculed the practices of the Jews and the "absurdity of their Law", making a mocking reference to how Ptolemy Lagus was able to invade Jerusalem in 320 BCE because its inhabitants were observing the *Shabbat*.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] One of the earliest anti-Jewish edicts, promulgated by Antiochus IV Epiphanes in about 170–167 BCE, sparked a revolt of the Maccabees in Judea.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] In view of Manetho's anti-Jewish writings, antisemitism may have originated in Egypt and been spread by "the Greek retelling of Ancient Egyptian prejudices".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] The ancient Jewish philosopher Philo of Alexandria describes an attack on Jews in Alexandria in 38 CE in which thousands of Jews died.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] The violence in Alexandria may have been caused by the Jews being portrayed as misanthropes.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Tcherikover argues that the reason for hatred of Jews in the Hellenistic period was their separateness in the Greek cities, the *poleis*.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Bohak has argued, however, that early animosity against the Jews cannot be regarded as being anti-Judaic or antisemitic unless it arose from attitudes that were held against the Jews alone, and that many Greeks showed animosity toward any group they regarded as barbarians.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Statements exhibiting prejudice against Jews and their religion can be found in the works of many pagan Greek and Roman writers.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Edward Flannery writes that it was the Jews' refusal to accept Greek religious and social standards that marked them out.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] There are examples of Hellenistic rulers desecrating the Temple and banning Jewish religious practices, including Antiochus IV Epiphanes, who in 167 BCE erected an altar to Zeus in the temple directed the sacrifice of pigs to at the altar.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] He also banned Jewish practices such as circumcision, Shabbat observance, and the study of Torah scrolls, sparking the Maccabean Revolt.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] The Jewish diaspora on the Nile island Elephantine, which was founded by mercenaries, experienced the destruction of its temple in 410 BCE.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Relationships between the Jewish people and the occupying Roman Empire were at times antagonistic and resulted in several rebellions, most notably the First Jewish–Roman War and the Bar Kokhba revolt.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] According to Suetonius, the emperor Tiberius took measures against Jews in Rome in 19 CE, expelling and relocating some Jewish‑affiliated groups in response to unrest and alleged religious‑moral offenses.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] The 18th-century English historian Edward Gibbon identified a more tolerant period in Roman–Jewish relations beginning in about 160 CE.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] However, with the rise of Christianity as the dominant religion, increasingly restrictive legislation and rhetoric was directed against Jews.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] James Carroll asserted: "Jews accounted for 10% of the total population of the Roman Empire.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] In the late 6th century CE, the newly Catholicised Visigothic kingdom in Hispania issued a series of anti-Jewish edicts which forbade Jews from marrying Christians, practicing circumcision, and observing Jewish holy days.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Continuing throughout the 7th century, both Visigothic kings and the Church were active in creating social aggression and towards Jews with "civic and ecclesiastic punishments", ranging between forced conversion, slavery, exile and death.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] From the 9th century, the medieval Islamic world classified Jews and Christians as *dhimmis* and allowed Jews to practice their religion more freely than they could do in medieval Christian Europe.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Under Islamic rule, there was a Golden age of Jewish culture in Spain that lasted until at least the 11th century.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] It ended when several Muslim pogroms against Jews took place on the Iberian Peninsula, including those that occurred in Córdoba in 1011 and in Granada in 1066.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Several decrees ordering the destruction of synagogues were also enacted in Egypt, Syria, Iraq and Yemen from the 11th century.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] In addition, Jews were forced to convert to Islam or face death in some parts of Yemen, Morocco and Baghdad several times between the 12th and 18th centuries.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] The Almohads, who had taken control of the Almoravids' Maghribi and Andalusian territories by 1147, were far more fundamentalist in outlook compared to their predecessors, and they treated the *dhimmis* harshly.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Faced with the choice of either death or conversion, many Jews and Christians emigrated.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Some, such as the family of Maimonides, fled east to more tolerant Muslim lands, while some others went northward to settle in the growing Christian kingdoms.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] In medieval Europe, Jews were persecuted with blood libels, expulsions, forced conversions and massacres.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] These persecutions were often justified on religious grounds and reached a first peak during the Crusades.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] In 1096, hundreds or thousands of Jews were killed during the First Crusade.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] This was the first major outbreak of anti-Jewish violence in Christian Europe outside Spain and was cited by Zionists in the 19th century as indicating the need for a state of Israel.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] In 1147, there were several massacres of Jews during the Second Crusade.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] The Shepherds' Crusades of 1251 and 1320 both involved attacks, as did the Rintfleisch massacres in 1298.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Expulsions followed, such as the 1290 banishment of Jews from England, the expulsion of 100,000 Jews from France in 1394, and the 1421 expulsion of thousands of Jews from Austria.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Many of the expelled Jews fled to Poland.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] As the Black Death epidemics devastated Europe in the mid-14th century, causing the death of a large part of the population, Jews were used as scapegoats.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Rumors spread that they caused the disease by deliberately poisoning wells.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Hundreds of Jewish communities were destroyed in numerous persecutions.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Although Pope Clement VI tried to protect them by issuing two papal bulls in 1348, the first on 6 July and an additional one several months later, 900 Jews were burned alive in Strasbourg, where the plague had not yet affected the city.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Martin Luther, an ecclesiastical reformer whose teachings inspired the Reformation, wrote antagonistically about Jews in his pamphlet *On the Jews and their Lies*, written in 1543.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] He portrays the Jews in extremely harsh terms, excoriates them and provides detailed recommendations for a pogrom against them, calling for their permanent oppression and expulsion.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] During the mid-to-late 17th century the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth was devastated by several conflicts, in which the Commonwealth lost over a third of its population (over 3 million people), and Jewish losses were counted in the hundreds of thousands.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] The first of these conflicts was the Khmelnytsky Uprising, when Bohdan Khmelnytsky's supporters massacred tens of thousands of Jews in the eastern and southern areas he controlled (today's Ukraine).
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] The precise number of dead may never be known, but the decrease of the Jewish population during that period is estimated at 100,000 to 200,000, which also includes emigration, deaths from diseases, and captivity in the Ottoman Empire, called *jasyr*.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] European immigrants to the United States brought antisemitism to the country as early as the 17th century.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Peter Stuyvesant, the Dutch governor of New Amsterdam, implemented plans to prevent Jews from settling in the city.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] During the Colonial Era, the American government limited the political and economic rights of Jews.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] It was not until the American Revolutionary War that Jews gained legal rights, including the right to vote.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] However, even at their peak, the restrictions on Jews in the United States were never as stringent as they had been in Europe.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] In the Zaydi imamate of Yemen, Jews were also singled out for discrimination in the 17th century, which culminated in the general expulsion of all Jews from places in Yemen to the arid coastal plain of Tihamah and which became known as the Mawza Exile.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] In 1744, Archduchess of Austria Maria Theresa ordered Jews out of Bohemia but soon reversed her position, on the condition that Jews pay for their readmission every ten years.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] This extortion was known among the Jews as *malke-geld* ("queen's money" in Yiddish).
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] In 1752, she introduced the law limiting each Jewish family to one son.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] In 1782, Joseph II abolished most of these persecution practices in his *Toleranzpatent*, on the condition that Yiddish and Hebrew were eliminated from public records and that judicial autonomy was annulled.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] According to Arnold Ages, Voltaire's "Lettres philosophiques, Dictionnaire philosophique, and Candide, to name but a few of his better known works, are saturated with comments on Jews and Judaism and the vast majority are negative".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] The counter-revolutionary Catholic royalist Louis de Bonald stands out among the earliest figures to explicitly call for the reversal of Jewish emancipation in the wake of the French Revolution.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Bonald's attacks on the Jews are likely to have influenced Napoleon's decision to limit the civil rights of Alsatian Jews.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Bonald furthermore declared that the Jews were an "alien" people, a "state within a state", and should be forced to wear a distinctive mark to more easily identify and discriminate against them.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Under the French Second Empire, the popular counter-revolutionary Catholic journalist Louis Veuillot propagated Bonald's arguments against the Jewish "financial aristocracy" along with vicious attacks against the Talmud and the Jews as a "deicidal people" driven by hatred to "enslave" Christians.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Between 1882 and 1886 alone, French priests published twenty antisemitic books blaming France's ills on the Jews and urging the government to consign them back to the ghettos, expel them, or hang them from the gallows.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Gougenot des Mousseaux's *Le Juif, le judaïsme et la judaïsation des peuples chrétiens* (1869) has been called a "Bible of modern antisemitism" and was translated into German by Nazi ideologue Alfred Rosenberg.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Thousands of Jews were slaughtered by Cossack Haidamaks in the 1768 massacre of Uman, in the Kingdom of Poland.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] In 1772, the empress of Russia, Catherine II, forced the Jews into the Pale of Settlement—which was located primarily in present-day Poland, Ukraine, and Belarus—and to stay in their shtetls and forbade them from returning to the towns that they occupied before the partition of Poland.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] From 1804, Jews were banned from their villages and began to stream into the towns.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] A decree by emperor Nicholas I of Russia in 1827 conscripted Jews under 18 years of age into the cantonist schools for a 25-year military service in order to promote baptism.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Policy towards Jews was liberalised somewhat under Czar Alexander II (r.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] However, his assassination in 1881 served as a pretext for further repression, such as the May Laws of 1882.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Konstantin Pobedonostsev, nicknamed the "black czar" and tutor to the czarevitch, later crowned Czar Nicholas II, declared that "One-third of the Jews must die, one-third must emigrate, and one third be converted to Christianity".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Historian Martin Gilbert writes that it was in the 19th century that the position of Jews worsened in Muslim countries.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Benny Morris writes that one symbol of Jewish degradation was the phenomenon of stone-throwing at Jews by Muslim children.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] In Jerusalem at least, conditions for some Jews improved.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] At the time of the Dreyfus trial in France, "Muslim comments usually favoured the persecuted Jew against his Christian persecutors".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] In 1850, the German composer Richard Wagner—who has been called "the inventor of modern antisemitism"—published *Das Judenthum in der Musik* (roughly "Jewishness in Music") under a pseudonym in the *Neue Zeitschrift für Musik*.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Although originally published anonymously, when the essay was republished 19 years later, in 1869, the concept of the corrupting Jew had become so widely held that Wagner's name was affixed to it.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Antisemitism can also be found in many of the Grimms' Fairy Tales by Jacob and Wilhelm Grimm, published from 1812 to 1857.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] It is mainly characterized by Jews being the villain of a story, such as in "The Good Bargain" ("*Der gute Handel*") and "The Jew Among Thorns" ("*Der Jude im Dorn*").
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] The middle 19th century saw continued official harassment of the Jews, especially in Eastern Europe under Czarist influence.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] For example, in 1846, 80 Jews approached the governor in Warsaw to retain the right to wear their traditional dress but were immediately rebuffed by having their hair and beards forcefully cut, at their own expense.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Even such influential figures as Walt Whitman tolerated bigotry toward the Jews in America.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] During his time as editor of the Brooklyn Eagle (1846–1848), the newspaper published historical sketches casting Jews in a bad light.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] The Dreyfus Affair was an infamous antisemitic event of the late 19th century and early 20th century.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Alfred Dreyfus, a Jewish artillery captain in the French Army, was accused in 1894 of passing secrets to the Germans.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] As a result of these charges, Dreyfus was convicted and sentenced to life imprisonment on Devil's Island.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] The actual spy, Marie Charles Esterhazy, was acquitted.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] The event caused great uproar among the French, with the public choosing sides on the issue of whether Dreyfus was actually guilty or not. Émile Zola accused the army of corrupting the French justice system.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] However, general consensus held that Dreyfus was guilty: 80% of the press in France condemned him.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] This attitude among the majority of the French population reveals the underlying antisemitism of the time period.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Adolf Stoecker (1835–1909), the Lutheran court chaplain to Kaiser Wilhelm I, founded in 1878 an antisemitic, anti-liberal political party called the Christian Social Party.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] This party always remained small, and its support dwindled after Stoecker's death, with most of its members eventually joining larger conservative groups such as the German National People's Party.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Some scholars view Karl Marx's essay "On The Jewish Question" as antisemitic, and argue that he often used antisemitic epithets in his published and private writings.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] These scholars argue that Marx equated Judaism with capitalism in his essay, helping to spread that idea.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Some further argue that the essay influenced National Socialist, as well as Soviet and Arab antisemites.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Marx himself had Jewish ancestry, and Albert Lindemann and Hyam Maccoby have suggested that he was embarrassed by it.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Others argue that Marx consistently supported Prussian Jewish communities' struggles to achieve equal political rights.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] These scholars argue that "On the Jewish Question" is a critique of Bruno Bauer's arguments that Jews must convert to Christianity before being emancipated, and is more generally a critique of liberal rights discourses and capitalism.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] David McLellan and Francis Wheen argue that readers should interpret *On the Jewish Question* in the deeper context of Marx's debates with Bruno Bauer, author of *The Jewish Question*, about Jewish emancipation in Germany.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Wheen says that "Those critics, who see this as a foretaste of 'Mein Kampf', overlook one, essential point: in spite of the clumsy phraseology and crude stereotyping, the essay was actually written as a defense of the Jews.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] It was a retort to Bruno Bauer, who had argued that Jews should not be granted full civic rights and freedoms unless they were baptised as Christians".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] According to McLellan, Marx used the word *Judentum* colloquially, as meaning *commerce*, arguing that Germans must be emancipated from the capitalist mode of production not Judaism or Jews in particular.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] McLellan concludes that readers should interpret the essay's second half as "an extended pun at Bauer's expense".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Between 1900 and 1924, approximately 1.75 million Jews migrated to America, the bulk from Eastern Europe escaping the pogroms.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] This increase, combined with the upward social mobility of some Jews, contributed to a resurgence of antisemitism.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] In the first half of the 20th century, in the US, Jews were discriminated against in employment, access to residential and resort areas, membership in clubs and organizations, and in tightened quotas on Jewish enrolment and teaching positions in colleges and universities.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] The lynching of Leo Frank by a mob of prominent citizens in Marietta, Georgia, in 1915 turned the spotlight on antisemitism in the United States.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] The case was also used to build support for the renewal of the Ku Klux Klan which had been inactive since 1870.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] At the beginning of the 20th century, the Beilis Trial in Russia represented modern incidents of blood-libels in Europe.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] During the Russian Civil War, close to 50,000 Jews were killed in pogroms.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Antisemitism in America reached its peak during the interwar period.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] The pioneer automobile manufacturer Henry Ford propagated antisemitic ideas in his newspaper *The Dearborn Independent* (published by Ford from 1919 to 1927).
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] The radio speeches of Father Coughlin in the late 1930s attacked Franklin D.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Roosevelt's New Deal and promoted the notion of a Jewish financial conspiracy.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Some prominent politicians shared such views: Louis T.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] McFadden, Chairman of the United States House Committee on Banking and Currency, blamed Jews for Roosevelt's decision to abandon the gold standard, and claimed that "in the United States today, the Gentiles have the slips of paper while the Jews have the lawful money".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] In Germany, shortly after Adolf Hitler and the Nazi Party came to power in 1933, the government instituted repressive legislation which denied Jews basic civil rights.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] These laws culminated in a state-sponsored pogrom on the night of 9–10 November 1938, known as Kristallnacht ("Night of Broken Glass"), during which at least 91 Jews were killed, thousands arrested, over 7,500 Jewish businesses destroyed, and about 1,400 synagogues burned or damaged.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Antisemitic legislation, agitation, and propaganda were subsequently extended to German-occupied Europe following the onset of war in 1939, frequently adapting or amplifying local antisemitic traditions (e.g., in Vichy France and occupied Poland).
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] In 1940, the famous aviator Charles Lindbergh and many prominent Americans led the America First Committee in opposing any involvement in a European war.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Lindbergh alleged that Jews were pushing America to go to war against Germany.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Lindbergh adamantly denied being antisemitic, and yet he refers numerous times in his private writings—his letters and diary—to Jewish control of the media being used to pressure the U.S. to get involved in the European war.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] In one diary entry in November 1938, he responded to *Kristallnacht* by writing "I do not understand these riots on the part of the Germans. ...
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] They have undoubtedly had a difficult Jewish problem, but why is it necessary to handle it so unreasonably?", acknowledgement on Lindbergh's part that he agreed with the Nazis that Germany had a "Jewish problem".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] An article by Jonathan Marwil in *Antisemitism, A Historical Encyclopedia of Prejudice and Persecution* claims that "no one who ever knew Lindbergh thought him antisemitic" and that claims of his antisemitism were solely tied to the remarks he made in that one speech.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] In the east the Third Reich forced Jews into ghettos in Warsaw, in Kraków, in Lvov, in Lublin and in Radom.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] After the beginning of the war between Nazi Germany and the Soviet Union in 1941, a campaign of mass murder, conducted by the Einsatzgruppen, culminated from 1942 to 1945 in systematic genocide: the Holocaust.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Eleven million Jews were targeted for extermination by the Nazis, and some six million were eventually killed.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] There have continued to be antisemitic incidents since WWII, some of which had been state-sponsored.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] In the Soviet Union, antisemitism was even used as an instrument for settling personal conflicts, starting with the conflict between Joseph Stalin and Leon Trotsky and continuing through numerous conspiracy theories spread by official propaganda.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Antisemitism in the USSR reached new heights after 1948 during the campaign against the "rootless cosmopolitan" (euphemism for "Jew") in which numerous Yiddish-language poets, writers, painters, and sculptors were killed or arrested.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] This culminated in the antisemitic conspiracy theory of the 'Doctors' Plot' in 1952.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] In the 20th century, Soviet and Russian antisemitism underwent significant transformations, shaped by political, social, and ideological shifts.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] During the early Soviet period, the Bolsheviks initially condemned antisemitism, seeing it as incompatible with Marxist ideology.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] However, under Joseph Stalin's regime, antisemitism reemerged, often cloaked in 'anti-Zionist' rhetoric.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] As early as 1943, Stalin and his propagandists intensified attacks against Jews as "rootless cosmopolitans".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] The Party issued confidential directives to fire Jews from positions of power, but state-controlled media did not openly attack Jews until the late 1940s.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] The Doctors' plot of 1952, a fabricated conspiracy accusing predominantly Jewish doctors of attempting to assassinate Soviet leaders, exemplified this resurgence.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] This campaign fostered widespread antisemitic sentiments and resulted in the arrest and execution of numerous Jewish professionals.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] In that same year, the antisemitic Slánský show trial alleged the existence of an 'international Zionist conspiracy' to destroy Socialism.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] The Six-Day War in 1967 led to an intensification in Soviet anti-Zionist propaganda as the Soviets had backed the defeated Arab states.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] This propaganda often blurred the lines with antisemitism, leading to discriminatory policies against Jews and restricting their emigration.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] By the end of the war, "the "corporate Jew", whether "cosmopolitan" or "Zionist", became identified as the enemy.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Their propaganda frequently borrowed directly from the forged Protocols of the Elders of Zion and sometimes relied upon Adolf Hitler's *Mein Kampf* as a source of information about Zionism.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Antizionism helped Moscow "bond both with its Arab allies and the Western hard left of all shades.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Similar antisemitic propaganda in Poland resulted in the flight of Polish Jewish survivors from the country.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] After the war, the Kielce pogrom and the "March 1968 events" in communist Poland represented further incidents of antisemitism in Europe.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] The anti-Jewish violence in postwar Poland had a common theme of blood libel rumours.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Antisemitism is still prevalent in contemporary far-right politics across much of the globe, whether as overt claims or covert dog-whistles.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Antisemitism has been a key factor for multiple perpetrators of far-right violence and terrorism in recent years, including the Pittsburgh synagogue shooting, the 2018 United States mail bombing attempts, and the Poway synagogue shooting.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Judith Butler, Masha Gessen, and others have identified a mainstreaming of Zionist antisemitism from the far-right under the Trump administrations in the US, with the Zionist Organization of America honouring Steve Bannon in 2017.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Holocaust denial, the claim that the Nazi genocide of European Jews during the Second World War either never happened or is substantially exaggerated by historical accounts, is a form of antisemitism and conspiracy theory.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Political movements seeking to revive the ideologies of the Nazis and other states that participated in the Holocaust, like neo-Nazism and neofascism, practice Holocaust denial.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Rehabilitation of Nazism can also be accomplished on an individual scale.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] There is significant debate about whether analogies between Israel's treatment of Palestinians and the Nazis' treatment of Jews or comparisons to Anti-Palestinianism are antisemitic.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Those who say they are antisemitic have termed such analogies "Holocaust inversion"—a form of Holocaust trivialisation, in which the Holocaust is compared with other events in a way that downplays its severity.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Deborah Lipstadt describes Holocaust inversion as a type of Holocaust denial.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Physical assaults against Jews in Europe have included beatings, stabbings, and other violence, which increased markedly, sometimes resulting in serious injury and death.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] This rise in antisemitic attacks is associated with both Muslim antisemitism and the rise of far-right political parties as a result of the economic crisis of 2008.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] This rise in the support for far-right ideas in western and eastern Europe has resulted in the increase of antisemitic acts, mostly attacks on Jewish memorials, synagogues and cemeteries but also a number of physical attacks against Jews.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Most of the antisemitic incidents in Eastern Europe are against Jewish cemeteries and buildings (community centers and synagogues).
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] According to Paul Johnson, antisemitic policies are a sign of a state which is poorly governed.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] While no European state currently has such policies, the Economist Intelligence Unit notes the rise in political uncertainty, notably populism and nationalism, as something that is particularly alarming for Jews.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Robert Bernstein, founder of Human Rights Watch, says that antisemitism is "deeply ingrained and institutionalized" in "Arab nations in modern times".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] In a 2011 survey by the Pew Research Center, all of the Muslim-majority Middle Eastern countries polled held significantly negative opinions of Jews.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] In the questionnaire, only 2% of Egyptians, 3% of Lebanese Muslims, and 2% of Jordanians reported having a positive view of Jews.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Muslim-majority countries outside the Middle East similarly held markedly negative views of Jews, with 4% of Turks and 9% of Indonesians viewing Jews favorably.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] According to a 2011 exhibition at the United States Holocaust Memorial Museum in Washington, United States, some of the dialogue from Middle East media and commentators about Jews bear a striking resemblance to Nazi propaganda.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] According to Josef Joffe of *Newsweek*, "anti-Semitism—the real stuff, not just bad-mouthing particular Israeli policies—is as much part of Arab life today as the hijab or the hookah.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Muslim clerics in the Middle East have frequently referred to Jews as descendants of apes and pigs, which are conventional epithets for Jews and Christians.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] According to professor Robert Wistrich, director of the Vidal Sassoon International Center for the Study of Antisemitism (SICSA), the calls for the destruction of Israel by Iran or by Hamas, Hezbollah, Islamic Jihad, or the Muslim Brotherhood, represent a contemporary mode of genocidal antisemitism.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] After the 2023 Hamas-led attack on Israel on 7 October and Israel's subsequent invasion of the Gaza strip, antisemitism and anti-Jewish hate crimes around the world increased significantly.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Multiple universities and university officials have been accused of systemic antisemitism.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] On 1 May 2024, the United States House of Representatives voted 320–91 in favour of adopting a bill enshrining the International Holocaust Remembrance Alliance definition of antisemitism into law.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] The bill was opposed by some who claimed it conflated criticism of Israel with antisemitism, while Jewish advocacy groups like the American Jewish Committee and World Jewish Congress generally supported it in response to the increase in antisemitic incidents on university campuses.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] An open letter by 1,200 Jewish professors opposed the proposal.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Extremist groups of Black Hebrew Israelites believe that Jewish people are "imposters", who have "stolen" Black Americans' true racial and religious identity.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Some of these groups also promote the unsupported Khazar hypothesis of Ashkenazi ancestry.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] In 2022, the American Jewish Committee stated that the Black Hebrew Israelite claim that "we are the real Jews" is a "troubling antisemitic trope with dangerous potential," arguing that such rhetoric perpetuates antisemitism by denying Jewish people's legitimacy as Jews.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] The perpetrators of several antisemitic attacks in the United States have expressed interest in the Black Hebrew Israelites.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Between 2019 and 2022, individuals motivated by Black Hebrew Israelites committed five religiously motivated murders.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] In September 2022, the Program on Extremism at George Washington University published a report which said the largest threat came from "individuals loosely affiliated with or inspired by the movement", rather than from formal members of Black Hebrew Israelite organizations.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Antisemitism has been explained in terms of racism, xenophobia, projected guilt, displaced aggression, conspiracy theory, and the search for a scapegoat.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] As another example, Walter Laqueur suggested that the antisemitic perception of Jewish people as greedy (as often used in stereotypes of Jews) probably evolved in Europe during medieval times where a large portion of money lending was operated by Jews.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Its foundation lies in the early claim of Jewish deicide and depictions of Jews as 'Christ-killers'.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Throughout Western history, Jews have since been used as a symbolic 'other' to define and articulate the values and boundaries of various cultures and intellectual traditions.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] In philosophy, literature, and politics, Jewishness has often been constructed as a counterpoint to what is considered normative or ideal.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] One of the key insights from Nirenberg's work is that antisemitism has proven to be remarkably adaptable.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] It changes form and adapts to different contexts and times, whether in medieval religious disputes, Enlightenment critiques, or modern racial theories.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Philosophers and intellectuals have often used 'Jewishness' as a foil to explore and define their ideas.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] For instance, in the Enlightenment, figures like Voltaire critiqued Judaism as backward and superstitious to promote their visions of reason and progress.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Similarly, the Soviet Union frequently portrayed Judaism as linked with capitalism and mercantilism, standing in opposition to the ideals of proletarian solidarity and communism.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] In each case, Judaism or the Jews are portrayed as standing in tension with prevailing moral norms.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] In it, Horn argues that antisemitism functions by appropriating what has happened to Jews and recasting their experience as part of a broader, universal struggle, which always ends in ultimately redefining Jewish identity as incompatible with these ideals.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] She concludes that the attacks on Jews, often under the guise of anti-Zionism, follow the same ancient pattern of marginalization and vilification.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Education plays an important role in addressing and overcoming prejudice and countering social discrimination.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Education equips learners with the knowledge to identify antisemitism and biased or prejudiced messages and raises awareness about the forms, manifestations, and impact of antisemitism faced by Jews and Jewish communities.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Some Jewish writers have argued that public education about antisemitism through the prism of the Holocaust is unhelpful at best or actively deepening antisemitism at worst.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Dara Horn wrote in *The Atlantic* that "Auschwitz is not a metaphor", arguing "That the Holocaust drives home the importance of love is an idea, like the idea that Holocaust education prevents anti-Semitism, that seems entirely unobjectionable.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] The Holocaust didn't happen because of a lack of love.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Instead, she argues that perhaps "a more effective way to address anti-Semitism might lie in cultivating a completely different quality, one that happens to be the key to education itself: curiosity.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Why use Jews as a means to teach people that we're all the same, when the demand that Jews be just like their neighbors is exactly what embedded the mental virus of anti-Semitism in the Western mind in the first place?
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] State Department found that there was an increase in antisemitism across the world, and that both old and new expressions of antisemitism persist.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights and Labor also noted a continued global increase in antisemitism, and found that Holocaust denial and opposition to Israeli policy at times was used to promote or justify blatant antisemitism.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] In August 2024, the Israeli Ministry of Diaspora Affairs announced a new antisemitism monitoring project.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] The goal of the project is to measure levels of antisemitism in various countries, as well as identify instigators and trends.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/antisemitic-p02] In the event that antisemitism in a given country becomes severe, the Diaspora Minister may contact that country's government in an official capacity.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Criticism has been directed at **Tesco** from various groups, including national organisations, trade bodies, individuals, consumer groups and watchdogs, particularly since the early 2000s.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] As with any large corporation, the Tesco supermarket chain is involved in litigation, usually from claims of personal injury from customers, claims of unfair dismissal from staff, and other commercial matters.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Criticism of Tesco includes disapproval of the effects supermarket chains can have on farmers, suppliers and smaller competitors; along with claims of generally poor labour relations with its staff concerning sick leave regulations.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Accusations concerning using cheap and/or child labour in Bangladesh amongst other places, have also arisen since the millennium.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] In 2006, the Office of Fair Trading (OFT) referred the UK grocery market to the Competition Commission for a new inquiry.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] In January 2007, the Competition Commission, published its initial findings into the UK grocery market.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] It said that they were "concerned with whether Tesco or any other supermarket can get into such a strong position, either nationally or locally, that no other retailer can compete effectively".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] It, however, found no actual basis for accusations that Tesco could use its land bank to control nearly half of national grocery retailing, and that suppliers' profits were being squeezed by the supermarket.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Tesco's 2004 Adminstore acquisition led to local and UK-wide protests.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Tesco's other store openings and expansions are sometimes contested by campaign groups.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] When a company controls more than 25% of a business sector in the UK, it is usually blocked from buying other companies in that sector (but not from increasing its market share through organic growth).
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] The Office of Fair Trading currently treats supermarkets and convenience stores as two distinct sectors—although this definition has been challenged by smaller retailers, including the Association of Convenience Stores.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] In February 2006, a group of UK MPs produced a report highlighting the near monopoly powers of the big four supermarkets.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] One problem discussed by the group was that of building without appropriate planning permission.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] The discussion stemmed from the company's building of a store in Stockport that was 20% larger than the company actually had permission to build.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] In September 2006, subsequent (retrospective) planning permission was requested by Tesco but refused.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] In April 2011, longstanding opposition to a Tesco Express store in Cheltenham Road, Stokes Croft, Bristol, evolved into a violent clash between opponents and police.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] The recently opened storefront was heavily damaged and the police reported the seizure of petrol bombs.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Opponents such as No Tesco in Stokes Croft, have suggested that the store would damage small shops and harm the character of the area.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] The group has been criticised for its tactics, including allegedly misleading consumers with "phoney" price cuts.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] For example, advertising huge savings, when in fact they are only lowering the price of less popular items and raising the price of more popular goods or misleading customers into believing that a sale price was a genuine reduction, and not the most common price.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Tesco is also censured by those who think that it infringes upon the interests of farmers and smaller suppliers.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] The company responds by claiming that it follows industry-best practice and sources locally where it can to meet customer demand.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] In March 2005, the Office of Fair Trading published an audit of the workings of its code of practice on relationships between supermarkets and their suppliers.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] A further report by the Office of Fair Trading in August 2005 concluded that the aims of the Code of Practice were being met.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] In September 2006, Tesco came to an agreement with Tyrrells Crisps to stop selling grey market supplies.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Tyrrells was founded by potato farmer Will Chase after big supermarkets' purchasing-power almost put his farm out of business.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] He started Tyrrells to gain greater margin by selling directly, and only sold through delicatessens and Waitrose supermarket.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] After Tesco bought supplies from the grey market, Chase sought legal advice but Tesco backed down.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Tesco denied squeezing its suppliers in December 2013 after retail analyst Cantor Fitzgerald accused Tesco of practices that risked breaching the Groceries Supply Code of Practice and criticised its trading relationships.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Similar accusations were also made in April 2005 despite its record £2,000,000,000 profit.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] American union leaders, representing employees of Tesco's Fresh & Easy brand, have complained that a "stark contrast" exists between the way the supermarket chain treats their British workers and staff at their US business.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] The two countries have differing legal regimes for labor unions.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] The UK trade union Usdaw relies upon a "partnership" model with large employers such as with Tesco, where there exists "privileged access" to the management of both organisations.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] In 2008 Tesco sued *The Guardian* for libel and malicious falsehood over the newspaper's claims that Tesco has developed a complex taxation structure involving offshore bank accounts in the tax haven of the Cayman Islands.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] The case was ultimately settled, with The Guardian issuing an apology.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] In 2014, the Serious Fraud Office and the Financial Reporting Council investigated Tesco's auditing and accounting practices, citing suspicions of accounting irregularities.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Tesco said it was "co-operating fully" with the SFO, who took matter out of the hands of the Financial Conduct Authority, the City's business regulator.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Tesco suspended eight executives during the investigation, including the UK corporate boss Chris Bush, and withheld payments worth £2,000,000 to its former chief executive Philip Clarke and chief financial officer Laurie McIlwee.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Tesco's auditor PwC declined to comment.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] The investigation concluded that profits were overstated by more than £250m over the course of several years.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Tesco has been criticised for charging higher prices for the same products at its Express stores.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Tesco has been accused of excessive profiteering during the 2021–present United Kingdom cost-of-living crisis.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Tesco has been criticised for selling customers' preferences and spending habits.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Tesco has been criticised for changing access to all its special offers to Clubcard customers only.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] In April 2023, the High Court ruled that Tesco was taking unfair advantage of competitor Lidl's discounter reputation with its Clubcard Prices logo design.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] In March 2024, Tesco lost an appeal it had infringed Lidl's trademark with its Clubcard Prices logo.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] In February 2024, Tesco agreed to include unit pricing for its Clubcard offers following criticism it was misleading customers.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] *Which?* had reported Tesco to the Competition and Markets Authority about the issue the previous year.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] In 2013, DNA tests revealed that horse meat was present in some meat products sold in Findus and ABP Food Group ready meals.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] On 7 February 2013, it was revealed by the Food Standards Agency that the Findus beef lasagne range in the UK, France and Sweden and the shepherd's pie and moussaka ranges in France contained horse meat without proper declaration or official scrutiny.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Ready packed meal firm Findus, Compass Group was the world's biggest catering firm at the time, and Whitbread, which was Britain's biggest hotel group, were indicted for illegally selling concealed horse meat in food products.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] As a result, Tesco's market capitalization dropped €360 million on Wednesday 16 January 2013.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Tesco, the Co-operative Group and Aldi also decided to cancel contracts with ABP Food Group because of the adulteration.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] In a public letter later that day, 11 firms, including Tesco and Asda, said they shared shoppers' "anger and outrage".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Whitbread vowed to remedy the unacceptable situation on 26 February.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] The Food Standards Agency's (FSA) chief executive, Catherine Brown also said "it is unlikely we will ever know" how many unwittingly ate horse meat.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] On 22 May 2007, the BBC's *Whistleblower* programme showed undercover footage detailing breaches of food hygiene rules in a branch of Tesco.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] The Whistleblower reporter applied for a job following a tip-off from a former employee.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Breaches included the sale of products after their sell-by date; allegations that the company illegally and sold 'back-labelled' products after their use by date; falsification of temperature records; and the sale of partially cooked mince mixed with uncooked mince.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] In addition to this the Food Safety Authority of Ireland, has on a number of occasions ordered the recall of Tesco branded products, including a case of glass contamination.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Environmental Health Officers served a closure order on Tesco's store in Prussia Street, Dublin, the day after they inspected it, for a number of breaches of Food Hygiene Regulations.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] In 2007, branches of Tesco and Sainsbury's were subject to claims of apparently out-of-date food being 'back-labelled' to appear still to be within date.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] In June 2008, it was revealed that Tesco had bought independent supermarket Brian Fords discount stores (with one store in Barnstaple, Devon, UK) five years previously, without notifying the public.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Tesco submitted planning applications for a new supermarket early in 2008 under Brian Fords' name.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] The plans included a Brian Fords sign and North Devon Council were said to be unaware of the Tesco takeover.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] It was later revealed that a separate property company, Wixley Properties Ltd (which had zero employees and zero turnover) had actually bought the supermarket.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Tesco said they were in control of Wixley Properties Ltd.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] In March 2016, Tesco came under fire for branding products with fictional farms names.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Later in the year the National Farmers Union lodged a complaint with Trading Standards over the matter.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] On 21 November 2020, a member of the Romanian diaspora in the United Kingdom pointed out that in one of Tesco's stores in London, there was a warning for shoplifters written in the Romanian language that said "notice for store thieves, you will be legally prosecuted if caught stealing".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] The Romanian women posted this on Facebook and called it "blatantly racist and xenophobic".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] She requested the removal of the poster, a petition that was joined by the Romanian Ministry of Foreign Affairs (MAE), which expressed its "surprise and disagreement against the strongly discriminating message".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] The news went viral and were later published in Romanian media.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] According to the Office for National Statistics, the Romanians in the United Kingdom then formed a community of about 427,000, making them the fourth largest foreign group in the country at the time.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] In June 2022, Tesco's adverts for one of its plant-based food ranges was banned for being misleading about their environmental benefit.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] In March 2024, Tesco faced significant criticism for delaying a promised pay rise, which left many employees earning less than the minimum wage for nearly a month.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] This delay allowed Tesco to save over £17 million.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] In 2024, Tesco was accused of using its wholesale subsidiary Booker Group to force the closure of local businesses and shops through undercutting their prices in Tesco stores, while providing higher prices in their wholesale arm.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Additionally, it has been accused of intentionally stopping deliveries of certain essential products to independent stores, in some cases reducing item selection by up to 30%.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Tesco Ireland is the largest food retailer in Ireland, with over 13,500 employees.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] As of 2004 Tesco Ireland has been criticised for apparently high prices in its Irish stores.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] This may be because comparisons are with the British Tesco stores rather than other Irish retailers – and thus like goods are not being compared with like.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] However, there have been general criticisms of the similar pricing between Irish supermarkets, and economic reports noting the high prices in Ireland generally.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Research concluded that only a five per cent difference in the cost of goods between North and South was justifiable.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] The findings highlighted retailers' larger margins in the South vis-a-vis their operations in the North, and the Minister for Enterprise, Trade and Employment queried why the price differential in many identical goods was substantially in excess of 5%.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Tesco in Ireland was convicted of failing to properly display prices by the National Consumer Agency in July 2008.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] A report by independent retailers group RGDATA contained allegations that Tesco overcharged customers.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] The report shows that customers in six Tesco stores were overcharged by an average of 3% on some items.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] In 2009, the Advertising Standards Authority determined Tesco's advertising was misleading.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] It claimed consumers could “save over 40%" but collectively the savings on the products advertised was less than 40%.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] In 2006, Tesco apologised for selling copies of the antisemitic forgery *The Protocols of the Elders of Zion*.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Sheikh Dr Shaheed Satardien, head of the Muslim Council of Ireland, described the sales as "polluting the minds of impressionable young Islamic people with hate and anger towards the Jewish community." Tesco also sold the material in the UK.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] In Autumn 2006, a Channel 4 News investigation found child labour in four Bangladesh garment factories supplying Tesco.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] War on Want published a report alleging that wages were as low as £0.05 (US$0.07) per hour for 80+ hour working weeks.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Tesco stated "All suppliers to Tesco must demonstrate that they meet our ethical standards on worker welfare, which are closely monitored.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Our suppliers comply with local labour laws, and workers at all Bangladeshi suppliers to Tesco are paid above the national minimum wage." Campaigners argued the minimum wage in Bangladesh is too low, and that monitoring systems used by clothing retailers, such as Tesco, are ineffective.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] In September 2011, Greenpeace reported supermarkets in China, including Tesco, were selling vegetables that contained illegal pesticides or others at levels exceeding safe limits.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Of 16 fruit and vegetable samples obtained from Tesco stores in Beijing and Guangzhou, 11 did not comply with regulations and one contained residues of methamidophos and monocrotophos, both of which had been prohibited since 2007.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] In December 2019, the BBC alleged Tesco's supply chain in China included forced prison labour.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] In 2010, two KDFSZ trade union officials that had persuaded a fellow employee and his family to report a serious accident were dismissed by Tesco Hungary.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Tesco claimed the officials had been "unethical and dishonest", and that they had "violated good faith and respectability".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] The Democratic Confederation of Free Trade Unions alleged Tesco breached Hungary's Labour Code requirements to consult with their trade union prior to the dismissals.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] In 2008, Thailand's Tesco Lotus associate sought penalties of two years in prison and a £16.4m libel damages from, writer and former legislator, Jit Siratranont after he argued it was expanding aggressively at the expense of small, local retailers.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Authors including Joanne Harris, Marina Lewycka and Deborah Moggach urged Tesco to "impress your critics with the force of argument, not the threat of imprisonment".
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] The criminal defamation and civil libel cases were dismissed by the Thai courts.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] Tesco Lotus brought similar actions against two other critics.
[src:criticism-of-tesco/criticism-of-tesco] It dropped one and settled the other in return for an apology.
